<HEADLINE> Kuwait Seeks Higher Oil Prices to Erase Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Oil-rich Kuwait is working
to achieve higher oil prices in the world market to help erase the
country's big budget deficit, a Kuwaiti oil official said here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The reasonable price for Brent crude should be 25-28 U.S.
dollars per barrel (dpb), said Kuwaiti Oil Minister Saud Nasser
Al-Sabah, quoted by official Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"Reaching this reasonable price is vital for our economy and we
are working to achieve it," Saud said.
</P>
<P>
He said if the price for Brent oil could reach the 25-28
dollars mark, "so when we calculate the average annual price, we
will conclude the price for Kuwaiti crude ranges between 20-21
dpb."
</P>
<P>
"This is the reasonable price of the Kuwaiti oil, which is
enough to erase the budget deficit of the current fiscal year,"
Saud said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's 4.25 billion dinars (14.025 billion dollars) budget
for 1999/2000 carries a gross deficit of 2.248 billion dinars
(7.418 billion dollars). The government based its projection of
the 1.761 billion dinars (5.811 bullion dollars) oil revenues on a
price of 10 dpb.
</P>
<P>
Saud was upbeat over a possible increase in oil prices. He said
prices will pick up as winter sales have not started yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
