<HEADLINE> Germans Celebrate Reunification Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Germans Sunday
celebrated the ninth anniversary of the reunification, both in the
city of Wiesbaden in the west and in the capital of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
In Wiesbaden, the celebration was featured with a speech of
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who said that German reunification
was far from fully realized, and there was still a huge gap
between Germans leaving in the west and those in the east.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a festivity to mark the national holiday, Schroeder
said, "Although the border between the west and the east has
disappeared, the economic and social borders still exist."
</P>
<P>
The building-up of the east needs Germans to pay more for the
solidarity until after the year 2004, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder called October 3 "the day of thanks to German
people." He praised the leading roles in the then West Germany for
their "solidarity and readiness to help (the east Germans)."
</P>
<P>
"That kind of solidarity is also required in the coming years,"
said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, also chairman of the Social Democratic Party (SPD),
called for more social equality in the German society.
</P>
<P>
"Only if people profit from society and have a say in its
workings, can Germany face the challenge of globalization," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Attending the ceremony were more than 1,000 people, including
President of the European Commission Romano Prodi, German
President Johannes Rau, and Wolfgang Thierse, president of the
German parliament's lower chamber, the Bundestag.
</P>
<P>
Noting Germany's importance in Europe's peace and stability,
Prodi said the difficulty in German reunification reflected the
problems in the eastward enlargement of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"The enlargement is not simple, but it gives Europe an
opportunity for peace and prosperity, after all those bleeding and
horrible conflicts in this century," said Prodi, who was the main
speaker at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He set the planned structural reform as a prerequisite of the
EU's enlargement, saying that the present institutions of the EU
were not able to manage a block of 25 or 30 member countries.
</P>
<P>
The new members in the future EU, Prodi said, would enjoy equal
rights just as the current members, since no "second class
membership" will be allowed in the EU.
</P>
<P>
Rau said in his speech that he was pleased with the progress in
the eastern states after the reunification.
</P>
<P>
"I have not yet forgotten the astonishment in German
reunification," said Rau, adding, "I am pleased by what the people
in the so-called new states have achieved during this period."
</P>
<P>
The ceremony in Wiesbaden, under the name of "common life,
common celebration," was held with a special church service
jointly by leading Protestant clergyman Peter Steinacker and his
Catholic counterpart, Franz Kamphause.
</P>
<P>
In Berlin, thousands of people rallied in the streets under the
motto of "Germany Celebrates 99 -- We're All of One Country."
</P>
<P>
Floats and groups in period costume depicting the 50-year
history of federal Germany, with mayor Eberhard Diepgen on head,
passed through the famous Brandenburg Gate before a street party
in the city got underway.
</P>
<P>
In the evening, the celebrations rounded off with a concert by
the Berlin Philharmonic conducted by Claude Abbado and attended by
Johannes Rau as a guest of honor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
