<HEADLINE> Finnish President Visits Syria on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Finnish President and current
Chairman of the European Council Martti Ahtisaari paid a one-day
state visit to Syria Sunday as part of a tour of Middle East
countries.
</P>
<P>
He was accompanied by Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen and
European Union (EU) Special Envoy to the Middle East Miguel Angel
Moratinos.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari was received by Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad at
the Damascus International Airport.
</P>
<P>
He held a meeting with Assad on the latest developments of the
Middle East peace process especially the efforts to resume the
Syrian-Israeli peace talks. Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa, Halonen and Moratinos attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The EU seeks to play a more effective role in the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari expressed his country's readiness to push forward the
peace process and solve the problems hindering it.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Assad pledged Syria's commitment to a fair and
comprehensive peace with a view to "restoring all rights to their
owners," according to the Syrian Television.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari and his party left here this evening after a
several-hour stay. They were seen off by Assad and high-ranking
Syrian officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
