<HEADLINE> Iran Intends to Free Hostage by Force: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Interior Ministry is
planning to use force to free the three Portuguese nationals
kidnapped by drug smugglers, an official of the ministry has said.
</P>
<P>
The official said "we will use force to teach a lesson to the
drug traffickers who must stop this sort of blackmailing," the
English daily Tehran Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The clan called "narooi" in Iran's southeastern province of
Sistan-Baluchistan, which is notorious for drug-trafficking, was
responsible for the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
"One of the clan members was arrested in Karaj with a huge
amount of morphine; the next day they kidnapped the three
portuguese near the Pakistani border," he said, adding that they
are demanding the release of the arrested narooi smuggler.
</P>
<P>
The official said every time a drug smuggler is arrested, they
kidnap some one; but he stressed "this time, we will teach a
lesson so that they do not repeat such a thing."
</P>
<P>
The three Portuguese nationals were taken hostage by drug
smugglers last month near the city of Zahedan, close to the
Pakistani border. This was the third kidnapping of foreigners in
four months.
</P>
<P>
In June, three Italians were abducted in southwestern Iran and
freed unharmed after a week in captivity.
</P>
<P>
In mid-August, the scenario was repeated. Four European tourists
and an Iranian national were abducted by suspected drug smugglers
in southeastern Iran and were released two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
Southeastern Iran is on the main route for drug smugglers
heading from Pakistan and Afghanistan to Europe. The so-called
Gold Crescent that overlaps parts of Iran, Pakistan and
Afghanistan, is one of the flagrant drug-producing areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
