<HEADLINE> Earthquake Rocks Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 4.1 on
the Richter scale rocked the Greek capital city of Athens Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the fresh aftershocks following the September 7
earthquake which had an epicenter in the Parnitha region, some 20
kilometers northwest of Athens.
</P>
<P>
A total of 143 people were killed and more than 2,000 others
injured and some 60,000 left homeless in the earthquake, which is
estimated to cost Greece more than 200 billion drachmas (about 645
million U.S. dollars)
</P>
<P>
Some 100 buildings collapsed in the earthquake and of the
buildings inspected by state engineers, around 40,000 have
sustained serious or slight damage.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are some different views in Greece that there
will be a possible strong earthquake in Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Van team had predicted that an earthquake registering
between 5 and 6 on the Richter scale would hit somewhere between
Athens and the central Greek city of Lamia by Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Van team, led by Prof. Panayiotis Varotsos, claims that it
can predict earthquakes by reading electrical activity in the
earth, but most seismologists and government officials say that
these findings can only be regarded as experiments and research
and cannot be seen as predictions as they are either vague or
mistaken on time, location and magnitude. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
