<HEADLINE> BOOT Helps Egypt Attract Foreign Capital: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
El-Ganzouri said on Sunday that implementing infrastructural
projects under the build-own-operate-transfer (BOOT) system
enables Egypt to pump foreign investments that are accompanied by
the most advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
El-Ganzouri made the remark at a signing ceremony of four
contracts between the Egyptian Electricity Authority and
Electricite de France (EdF) on the building of two power stations
under the BOOT system.
</P>
<P>
He said the BOOT system helps Egypt curb borrowing from foreign
countries and international financial institutions or imposition
of new taxes or dues aimed at amassing funds for infrastructural
construction.
</P>
<P>
Building infrastructure projects such as power stations,
seaports, airports and roads under the BOOT system reflects
President Hosni Mubarak's keenness on building the foundations of
development for the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
The BOOT system has helped Egypt attract billions of dollars of
foreign investments in the fields including industry, agriculture
and tourism, a move that reflects the confidence of other
countries in Egypt's economic policy and political stability, the
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Under the contracts, EdF will invest 750 million dollars in the
building of two power stations in each of East Port Said and
Suez. Each of the stations has a capacity of 650 megawatts. EdF
will run the power station and sell the product to Egypt in a
period of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Electricity Authority has planned to invite
foreign investors to build more than 10 power stations in this way
before 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
