<HEADLINE> Germany Welcomes Expansion of Ties With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- German Deputy Economy Minister
Axel Gerlaq said here Sunday that Germany welcomes expansion of
ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 25th Tehran International Fair, Gerlaq said
that Germany is prepared to increase import of Iranian goods, but
he stressed that Germany-Iran ties have not had the necessary
stability in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Germany were cooled down in April
1997 after a Berlin court accused Iran of sponsoring assassination
of four Iranian Kurdish leaders in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court rule triggered a diplomatic row between Iran
and members of the European Union (EU), which recalled their
ambassadors from Tehran in a protest. The two sides ended their
dispute in November 1997 after the EU states agreed to return
their ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
Gerlaq, who is in Tehran for the Tehran International Fair,
said that Iranian goods are facing intense competition from other
countries in Europe and new ideas are needed to ensure success in
European markets.
</P>
<P>
German Ambassador to Iran Klaus Celler expressed satisfaction
with Iranian President Mohammad Khatami's visit to the German
pavilion at the fair and hoped that Khatami will visit Germany
upon an invitation of the German chancellor.
</P>
<P>
He also said participation of more than 100 German companies in
the ongoing trade fair in Tehran reflects Germany's interest in
strengthening bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Germany is Iran's largest trade partner in west Europe, with
Germany's exports to Iran reaching 1.7 billion U.S. dollars last
Iranian year ending March 20 this year and Iran's non-oil products
exports to the European state amounting to 410 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
