<DOCNO> XIE19991004.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millions of Tanzanians Pray for Nyerere's Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Millions of Tanzanians
continue to pray for the ailing former president Julius Nyerere a
quick recovery.
</P>
<P>
People in northern town Arusha prayed at churches, mosques and
temples for Nyerere who is admitted at St. Thomas!/ Hospital in
London for leukemia and other health complications.
</P>
<P>
The Arusha Regional Commissioner, Daniel Ole Njoolay, led the
prayers Sunday at a Lutheran Church. They all wished Nyerere,
revered as the founding father, an early recovery and God to grant
him special strength so that he could overcome his illness and
come back home safely.
</P>
<P>
In the capital Dar es Salaam, Azania Front Lutheran Church and
several others in the city conducted prayers for Nyerere, a major
figure in post- colonial Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Youth General Council Executive Committee of the ruling
Chama Cha Mapinduzi, which ended its two-day session in Dar es
Salaam Sunday, expressed concern over Nyerere's health and wished
him quick recovery and good health.
</P>
<P>
The committee conducted special prayer for Nyerere, 77, and
appealed to all youth countrywide to pray for him in response to a
call made by President Benjamin Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
According to two bulletins released by the State House Sunday,
doctors attending Nyerere said that there is every possibility for
Nyerere to recover. However, they said his critical condition has
not changed.
</P>
<P>
The doctors said they have so far managed to control some of
his health complications, and X-ray checks indicated that most of
the important parts of his body are stable and jaundice
complications are decreasing.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa telephoned the elderly African statesman's wife
Maria Nyerere, who is at the bedside of his husband, and wished
Nyerere all the best. The government has vowed to try all means to
save the founding father' s life, government spokesman Geoffrey
Nkurlu said.
</P>
<P>
The first lady Anna Mkapa is also offering help at the
hospital, together with three sons and two daughters of Nyerere,
who was admitted to the hospital nine days ago.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere led the then Tanganyika to independence from Britain in
1961 and masterminded its union Zanzibar isles in 1964 to form
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
After retiring as president in 1985, he played an advisory role
in both Tanzanian politics and African affairs. He tirelessly
mediated Burundi peace talks since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere is addressed throughout Africa as Mwalimu, or teacher
in Kiswahili, for his wisdom and integrity.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Administration and Local Government, Kingunge
Ngombale-Mwiru, is in London administering issues concerning
Nyerere in collaboration with Tanzanian High Commission in
Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
