<HEADLINE> UK, Ireland, U.S. Sign Cancer Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The British, Irish and American
governments signed an agreement in Belfast, Britain, Sunday to
coordinate efforts to combat cancer.
</P>
<P>
According to a Reuters report filed from Belfast, former U.S.
senator George Mitchell, who is mediating in Northern Ireland's
peace process, chaired the signing of the deal by health ministers
from Dublin, Belfast and Washington.
</P>
<P>
The deal will result in the development of joint cancer
research projects and staff exchange programs, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The cancer consortium will be administered by a governing board
comprising the chief medical officers of Northern Ireland, the
Republic of Ireland and the U.S. National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 cancer experts are due to attend a three-day
international cancer conference in Belfast Monday, with half of
the delegates coming from the United States, according to Reuters.
</P>
</TEXT>
