<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Place New Ceiling on Age of Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus announced here Sunday
that as of 1 January 2000 it will introduce a new policy for the
registration of ships under the Cyprus flag, placing a new ceiling
on the age of ships.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Cyprus' Minister of
Communications and Works Averof Neophytou, at the opening of a
four-day international meeting on shipping.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, attended by some 1,000 delegates from 35
countries, will deal with international brokering, ship finance,
the tanker industry, marine insurance, European Union (EU) safety
policy and use of information technology in shipping.
</P>
<P>
"Under the new policy there is a new ceiling on the age of
ships which may be registered while the age of ships for which an
entry inspection is required is lowered from 17 to 15 years,"
Averof said.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus in its effort to improve quality has appointed
additional professional staff at the Department of Merchant
Shipping and has expanded the network of independent surveyors.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, he said, has decided to allocate all is resources in
the next two years to "safety, pollution prevention and adequate
manning standards" rather than growth.
</P>
<P>
The minister described the International Maritime Organization
as "a prime example of a U.N. organization where so much has been
achieved with regard to maritime safety and the protection of the
marine environment through cooperation and consensus among member
states."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has 2,667 ships registered under its flag with a
combined tonnage of 26.5 million gross tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
