<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses U.N. Committee of Blocking Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Trade Ministry on Sunday
accused the U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking four of its
contracts signed under the oil-for-food program, Iraqi News
Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman for the ministry blamed the U.S. and
British representatives at the Sanctions Committee for suspending
those four contracts during the committee's session held on
September 28.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said these blocked contracts were signed with
companies of Italy and France and included engineering equipment,
educational prerequisites, medical appliances and spare parts for
the oil sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, now in its sixth phase which
expires in November, Iraq is allowed to sell limited amount of
oil in every six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
Since the fourth phase of the deal, the ceiling of the limited
amount of oil has been raised to 5.2 billion dollars from 2
billion for the first three phases.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long accused the U.S. and British envoys in the
Sanctions Committee of hampering the endorsement of its
contracts, arguing that the oil-for-food deal has failed to
alleviate the sufferings of the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
