<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA, Israel to Meet Again over Passage Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli-Palestinian Safe
Passage Committee is scheduled to meet again Sunday evening to try
to iron out differences over the opening of the southern safe
passage route.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, local government minister of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) and Mohammed Dahlan, PNA preventive
security chief in Gaza and Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo
ben-Ami will join the meeting, it is learned.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami said earlier Sunday that the committee can soon settle
the contentious issues.
</P>
<P>
The southern safe passage that links Gaza and Tarkumia near the
West Bank city of Hebron was scheduled to open on October 1 under
the lastest Palestinian-Israeli peace deal, or the Sharm al-Sheikh
Memorandum. The opening date was reset for Sunday because of
Jewish holidays on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But earlier in the day, Orit Messer-Harel, spokeswoman of the
Israeli Public Security Ministry, announced to postpone the
opening again, saying the two sides failed to settle differences
over some major issues after five hours of talks Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
She said the major sticking points were which side and where to
issue the corridor passes and whether Israel is entitled to arrest
Palestinians suspected of security offenses as they use the
passage.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side wants to be the ultimate issuing authority
for the passes. Israeli newspapers reported that Israel wants to
maintain control in order to prevent forgeries by militants
planning attacks.
</P>
<P>
The delay in the passage opening is the first major setback in
the implementation of the Sharm al-Sheikh Memorandum signed last
month by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
