<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Calls for Settlement Through Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister of Bangladesh
Sheikh Hasina Sunday asked opposition leader Begum Khaleda Zia to
fix up her demands first and then settle those through discussion
with the government.
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything possible for the welfare of the country
through discussions," she said while addressing a huge public
meeting in Kachua, about 370 kilometers to the southeast of Dhaka,
according to Bangladesh News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister reiterated her commitment that the ruling
Awami League would never call hartal (destructive strike) even if
it goes to opposition.
</P>
<P>
She said that stability is a pre-requisite for development and
the frequent hartals destroy the stability.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan, secretary general of the
Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), the main opposition party of
the country, on Sunday reiterated the opposition's demand for
resignation of the government and handing over of power to a
caretaker authority to arrange fresh parliamentary polls.
</P>
<P>
He repeated this demanded when addressing a post-hartal
briefing here on Sunday night. The opposition has announced fresh
anti-government programs, including countrywide "anti-aggression
day" on October 11, to protest the "Indian aggression" and "the
government's silence" over the Indian Border Security Force
aggression along the country's border.
</P>
<P>
The clashes during the opposition-enforced down-to-dust hartal,
which ended this evening, left one killed and at least 50 persons
injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
