<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebels Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone rebel leaders Foday
Sankoh and Johnny Koroma Sunday returned home on Sunday for the
first time since the Lome peace deal was signed in July.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh and Koroma flew in on a Nigerian government plane from
Liberia, where they held two-day talks on their strained
relations.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, in a white African robe, stepped down from the plane
and said: " We are here. We are here," according to reports
reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two rebel leaders, accompanied by regional and
international officials including Nigeria's Minister for
Cooperation and Integration in Africa Jerry Gana, were greeted by
small group of officials and supporters at the Lungi airport,
north of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
An other plane brought in senior aides, rebel field commanders
and their families earlier Sunday, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh and Koroma were back to take their positions in a unity
government with President Tejan Kabbah, as designated by the July
7 peace agreement, which hopefully will consolidate the
hard-earned peace in the small west Africa country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
