<HEADLINE> Iraqi Vice President's Visit to Egypt Private: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The current visit by an Iraqi vice
president to Egypt has "no political implications," a top Iraqi
diplomat in Cairo said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Taha Moheidin Maarouf's visit is private and has no plans to
meet Egyptian officials, Iraq's permanent representative to the
Arab League Sultan al-Shawi told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Maarouf arrived here unexpectedly Saturday on a flight of Royal
Jordanian from Amman, Jordan, Egypt's Al-Akhbar daily reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Reports quoted some Arab diplomats as saying that Maarouf came
here apparently for medical treatment and he may hold talks with
Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
Terming the reports "totally void of truth," al Shawi said
there are no arrangements for him to meet Egyptian officials
during his 7-10 days of stay here.
</P>
<P>
Maarouf is the highest-ranking Iraqi official to visit Egypt
since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, which triggered the 1991
Gulf War. The two countries severed diplomatic relations over
Egypt's participation in the Gulf War against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Foreign Ministry has also confirmed that Maarouf
is in Cairo on a private visit.
</P>
<P>
Maarouf is not considered as part of Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein's inner circle. But his diplomatic credits are respected
in Iraq. Before the Gulf War, Maarouf served as Saddam's emissary
to foreign leaders, including Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
