<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Detent Foreign Policy Welcomed: Kharrazi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has said that Iran's foreign policy of detent and
confidence-building has been welcomed by world states.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi, who returned here Saturday after attending the 54th
session of the United Nations General Assembly in New York, said
all foreign leaders he talked with expressed their countries'
readiness to further expand relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Since the moderate President Mohammad Khatami came to power in
1987, Iran has been pursuing a policy of detent in order to
improve ties with the rest of the world and effectively break the
isolation following the victory of the 1979 Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Iran has so far reached rapprochement with some Gulf Arab
neighbors and normalized relations with European countries.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that during his talks on the fringes of the
U.N. meeting, he had in mind plans for further promoting economic
ties with foreign countries and activating engagement of Iran's
private sector in the process.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency Sunday, Kharrazi, during
his stay in New York, attended the sideline meetings of foreign
ministers of the Organization of the Islamic Conference, the Group
of 77 developing countries, and the Non-aligned Movement.
</P>
<P>
At the meetings, he outlined the Iranian government's stances
towards international developments as well as issues of the
Islamic world, the Islamic Republic News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi and his counterparts discussed different international
and regional crises in the Middle East, East Timor, central Asia
and Caucasus, Iraq and Afghanistan, global disarmament and fight
against drugs, among other topics.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister also held talks with U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
