<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Lashes out at Israel's Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa on Sunday lashed out at Israel's policy on continuing
expansion of Jewish settlements in the occupied Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israel's decision to expand settlements, Moussa
told reporters that this step is detrimental to the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks and the general atmosphere of the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt has urged the United Nations to adopt a
resolution that will denounce Israel's settlement activities as an
obstacle to the peace process. He called on other countries to
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is cautiously optimistic about the Palestinian-Israeli
peace negotiations due to Israel's settlement policy, the foreign
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Israeli relations soured in 1996 when former
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's settlement policy
stalled the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Although the bilateral relations have been improved after the
moderate Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak took power in July,
Egypt is critical of Israel's hardline policies.
</P>
<P>
The settlement issue, among other things, is much at the core
of the final status negotiations between the Palestinians and
Israel, which began on September 13. The two sides have agreed not
to take unilateral actions before reaching a final peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moussa dismissed as baseless a report by the Israeli
Yediot Ahronot newspaper that Egypt, the United States, Israel,
Jordan and the Palestinian National Authority have agreed to
cooperate in combating terrorism in the region.
</P>
<P>
The report is not true and misleading, and is aimed at causing
confusion, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel. But alongside other Arab countries, it has vowed not to
forge significant cooperation with the Jewish state until a
durable and comprehensive peace is realized in the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
