<HEADLINE> Canadian Fishermen Clash Over Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Non-native fishermen clashed with
their native counterparts in Canada's Atlantic province of New
Brunswick Sunday night over the controversial rights on off-season
catch of lobsters.
</P>
<P>
Non-native fishermen' protest turned into violence of pulling
up and cutting lobster traps of the natives at Miramichi Bay. An
angry mob later stormed three local fish plants, destroying
computers, vending machines and refrigerators, Canadian media said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two trucks owned by non-natives were set on fire on the Burnt
Church Reserve, where a crowd of native fishermen were gathering.
Local authorities have not yet confirmed if it was a retaliation
by natives.
</P>
<P>
Police urged calm from both sides and demanded they start to
find solutions to the problem by dialogue and communication.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have remained high in New Brunswick following a
Supreme Court ruling last month that allows natives to fish out of
season and without a license to earn a moderate livelihood, local
media said.
</P>
<P>
Non-native fishermen are worried that lobster stocks could be
depleted by the time they are allowed to open fishery next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
