<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Hit Out at Tajikistan "Interference" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban
Tuesday warned Tajikistan not to "play with fire" by supporting
Afghan opposition, threatening "grave consequences".
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the religious militia's foreign ministry
accused Tajikistan of allowing the anti-Taliban alliance led by
Tajik ethnic Ahmad Shah Masood to use Tajik territory for supply
routes to their supporters.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Taliban groups use Tajikistan's Kolyab airbase close to
the Afghan border while Tajik ships carry military supplies to
Masood through a newly-built crossing point on the Oxus river into
the opposition base in Takhar province, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan, once again stressing its
desire of having friendly relations with all countries,
particularly the neighbors, seriously warns the Dushanbe regime
rulers that they will face grave consequences of playing with this
fire," it said.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Emirate, as the legitimate state of Afghanistan,
reserves the right to react as required in order to counter
foreign interference," the strongly-worded statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have controlled over 80 percent of the territory of
Afghanistan during their five-year-long war against the opposition
alliance, but the regime of Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan it
established has been recognized only by three Islamic countries
including Saudi Arabia, Pakistan and UAE.
</P>
<P>
At the U.N. General Assembly last week, Tajikistan urged the
world body to consider imposing sanctions against those, in a
direct reference to the Taliban, who "violate the resolutions of
the Security Council and the General Assembly".
</P>
<P>
Last December the Security Council issued a resolution,
demanding the warring Afghan factions enter peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan's demand for sanctions is "another sign of Dushanbe
rulers' enmity with the Afghan nation ..." the foreign ministry
statement added.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan shares a 1,500-kilometer border with Afghanistan
which is guarded by Russian soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
