<HEADLINE> Eight Injured in Clash Between Police, Kashmiri Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 4 (Xinhua) -- At least eight people were
injured Monday during a clash between Pakistan's police and
Kashmiri activists who made an attempt to cross the Line of
Control (LoC) in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Muzaffarabad, capital of Pakistan-administered
Kashmir, said that police fired bullets in the air and used
teargas shells to stop a march by activists from the Jammu and
Kashmir Liberation Front (JKLF) across LoC.
</P>
<P>
JKLF supporters gathered at Hajira, 12 kilometers west of LoC
which divides the disputed Kashmir area despite a security
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Yasin, spokesman for the JKLF, claimed that police
fired bullets on the activists who were holding a peaceful
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani authorities banned the planned crossing, saying
it will prompt retaliatory attacks by Indian soldiers stationed
along LoC.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that a crowd of about 1,000 people was able to
force its way through police hurdles and marched toward Midarpur
village close to LoC.
</P>
<P>
The JKLF spokesman claimed that police had detained more than
2,000 of their activists during the last four days. About 200
people were arrested on Monday, said Yasin.
</P>
<P>
Police sources, however, said that they had detained 120 people
in the last four days to stop the march across LoC.
</P>
<P>
The JKLF planned the march to oppose the existence of the
military LoC drawn in 1972 after the last of three wars between
the rival South Asian neighbors of Pakistan and India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
