<HEADLINE> More Thai Troops Leave for East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Two hundred and twenty-one Thai
soldiers bound for East Timor left here Monday for Darwin,
Australia, which is the International Force for East Timor
(INTERFET)'s staging point.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, 115 Thai soldiers and their equipment already
left for the same destination.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, who saw the 221 soldiers off
at the military airport in Bangkok, asked the soldiers to make
their contributions to the peace and stability of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the Thai Army's Rapid Deployment Force Colonel
Noppadol Charoenporn was quoted by Thai News Agency (TNA) as
saying earlier Monday that he had told Thai troops that their duty
was not to fight anybody but to restore peace and order in the
territory.
</P>
<P>
The use of force would not be the soldiers' priority, the
colonel said.
</P>
<P>
According to TNA, the troops were also told that gambling,
smoking, drinking and courting women would be strictly forbidden
during their mission in the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has agreed to send a total of 1,581 military personnel
to join the INTERFET and the country's Major General Songkitti
Jaggabatra has been appointed deputy commander of the
multinational force.
</P>
<P>
An advance group of 33 people had left Thailand on September
17, while the rest of the 1,581 troops to join the Australian-led
mission in the troubled territory will depart in the next two to
three weeks by October 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
