<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Not to Implement Extra Gov. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo will not implement extra spending approved by the
National Assembly to maintain financial stability as Nigeria
rebuilds its economy after 15-year military rule, a Nigerian
newspaper quoted government sources as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The legislature approved a 22 percent increase in spending on
 government ministries on Thursday over the original budget
proposed by Obasanjo in July, according to the Vanguard newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"If we used the budget the National Assembly has approved then
it would mean releasing so much money that inflation would really
rise. It would really be out of control," said one senior
government official. "We are not prepared to see that happen," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo's revised budget severely cut back government
commitments after the military pushed the deficit to 2.5 billion
US dollars before they stepped down in May.
</P>
<P>
The budget cuts were one-point in Nigeria's favour in
discussions with international financial institutions, which were
otherwise worried about the slow pace of privatization, continued
subsidies and an unwillingness to allow a market-determined
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
But the National Assembly said the rise in oil export prices to
more than 21 US dollars per barrel from around 10 dollars at the
start of the year meant Nigeria could afford to loosen the purse
strings a little to restart the damaged economy.
</P>
<P>
The country's top legislature approved an increase in the
budget to 462. 8 billion naira (4.87 billion U.S. dollars) from
June to the end of 1999, compared to the 443.3 billion naira (4.66
billion U.S. dollars) proposed by Obasanjo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
