<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia has extended 5.77 billion U.S. dollars
of aid to developing states from 1974 to 1998, according to the
annual report of the Saudi Development Fund.
</P>
<P>
The report issued Monday said that 39 African countries got
2.68 billion dollars, 19 developing states in Asia obtained about
2.98 billion and five states in other parts of the world received
about 110 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of State for Planning and
International Cooperation Zafer el-Beshri has said that the
U.S. government has approved the assistance program for Egypt for
1999, which amounts to 971 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The minister said 859.7 million dollars of aid will given to
Egypt in 28 agreements that came into effect Sunday. Another 111
million dollars will be extended to Egypt this year out of the
credit lines of the monetary transfer agreements, the Arabic Al
Wafd newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria's wheat production in the last season has
dropped by about 1.3 million tons, resulting in a decline of
900,000 tons in wheat stockpile.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural experts attributed the decline to rainfall
scarcity last winter which was 60 percent below the average level,
the Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The official sources said the Crop Marketing Authority bought a
total of 1.7 million tons of wheat in the last season, as compared
with last year's 2.7 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The sources anticipate that total wheat production by the end
of the season will amount to 2.7 million tons, but it is also less
than last year's 4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia will invest a total of 1.5 billion dollars for
the development of the communications sector during the ninth
development plan that ends by the end of year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia invested over 860 million dollars in the sector in the
eighth development plan.
</P>
<P>
The communications sector has been steadily growing at a high
rate in recent years. According to the Ministry of Communications,
the sector is expected to grow by 17 percent during the current
development plan and the growth rate was 15 percent in last one.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The World Oil Refining Association in association
with the Abu Dhabi National Oil Co. (Adnoc), will be holding an
"Oil Refining and Petrochemicals in the Middle East" conference
here on October 25-26.
</P>
<P>
The conference will bring together key personnel in the
downstream sector and is the only event focusing on refining and
petrochemicals, said the latest issue of Adnoc News.
</P>
<P>
The event will cover the two most important aspects of the oil
refining industry - business and finance and technology
development, the publication said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
