<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Observes World Animal Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua)-- Nearly 400 people took their pets
to a playful gathering at Beijing's Changping Stadium for World
Animal Day today.
</P>
<P>
Dogs got acquainted with each other and showed off their skills
by baying at a microphone to the accompaniment of a Chinese bamboo
flute, bowing, standing up, getting leather balls, and jumping
through a hoop.
</P>
<P>
Pet food companies and hospitals for vegetarian pets had stands
around the soccer field demonstrating their products and services.
The gathering was sponsored by the Beijing Small Animal
Association and was the fourth such annual gathering in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Association's president Geng Binjin said at an opening
ceremony that the purpose of the activity was to provide a chance
for animal lovers to get together and to increase awareness of the
need to protect animals and to share nature with animals.
</P>
<P>
Pets have become a major part of leisure time in China since
the late 1970s when China started its reforms and opening up. But,
because of a lack of awareness of pet care and government
restrictive measures like registration fees and annual maintenance
fees that amount to several times the purchase price of a dog, the
pet population is much smaller than it is in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Zu Shuxian, a professor at Anhui University of Medical Sciences,
is one of the people promoting pets in the household, who argues
that keeping pets is good for humans physically and
psychologically.
</P>
<P>
October 4 was designated World Animal Day in the 1920s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
