<HEADLINE> Israel's Parliament Opens Winter Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- After a two-month summer
recession, Israel's 15th Knesset (parliament) opened its winter
session Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
More than 650 bills are already in the legislative pipeline
and awaiting considerations, according the Knesset secretariat,
but the central issue the current Knesset faces in the coming days
is the passage of the new government budget.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has not yet submit the budget to the
Knesset, Knesset Speaker Avraham Burg said prior to the opening of
the session that the vote on the budget must be end by December
31, to enable a shutdown of computers for a few days to avoid
possible effects from the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
Burg also said that he would help push for the passage of the
law regarding the reform of the electoral system.
</P>
<P>
The central point of this law requests that ministers should
resign their Knesset seats, be replaced by the persons next in
line on their party's Knesset list.
</P>
<P>
Burg said he would also support the advancement of Justice
Minister Yossi Beilin's legislation to cancel the system of
direct elections, as part of a package of constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset has 120 members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
