<HEADLINE> Thailand, Cambodia to Address Health Problems Along Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Cambodia have
agreed to cooperate in tackling health problems along the border,
the Thai News Agency quoted a senior Thai Public Health Ministry
official as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
Supachai Kunaratanapruek, deputy permanent secretary for public
health, said that the agreement was reached at a recent meeting
on border health problems between Thai and Cambodian health
officials.
</P>
<P>
The two sides managed to determine a clear-cut framework on
public health cooperation, which will not only help solve
communicable diseases and other health problems along the border,
but also strengthen bilateral relations, Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Bangkok and Phnom Penh would exchange
information on a regular basis to control communicable disease
along the border and would jointly address problems of public
health service management, including control of food and medicines
and other related issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to cooperate in human resource
development in the field of public health, and in the improvement
of public health facilities through a three-level task force that
the two countries agreed to set up.
</P>
<P>
Key health problems along the Thai-Cambodian border reportedly
include malaria, AIDS and insufficient quality and standard of
medicines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
