<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economy Tops List of Public Concerns in HK: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Problems relating to the
economy have reclaimed the top spot in Hong Kong, replacing labor
issues which have been the public's leading concern in the past
four months.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of people who mentioned economy-related problems
has gone up from 43 percent to 51 percent in the September survey,
the latest bimonthly public opinion investigation conducted by the
Home Affairs Bureau (HAB) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Whereas labor-related issues, which had been the problem most
often mentioned in the last two surveys, were relegated to the
number two slot.
</P>
<P>
"This may have to do with the higher number of job vacancies
registered with the Labor Department and the fact that the Health
and Welfare Bureau is considering relaxing the restrictions on
income and hours of work for Comprehensive Social Security
Assistance applications," an HAB spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"There also appeared to be a correlation between economic and
labor issues as among those who mentioned economy-related problems,
51 percent were also concerned about the current employment
situation, which is higher than in the last survey of 47 percent,"
the spokesman observed.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of survey respondents who mentioned labor-
related problems had gone down from 45 percent in July to 38
percent in this survey. Of this group, 95 percent, down by one
percentage point, reported difficulty in finding jobs, layoffs or
underemployment.
</P>
<P>
Housing, at 22 percent, up from 15 percent, remained the third
most often mentioned problem.
</P>
<P>
Some findings of the survey remained relatively unchanged,
including the 32 percent who expressed satisfaction with the
overall performance of government, the 44 percent who were happy
with the present situation and the 60 percent who were confident
that Hong Kong would continue to be prosperous and stable.
</P>
<P>
The survey is the 84th in the series which started in January
1983. It resulted from the successful interviewing by telephone of
1,447 respondents aged 15 to 64 who were chosen by random from the
residential telephone directories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
