<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Need 2.1 Million Houses by 2006 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now 11.4 percent of Ugandan population live in urban areas and
the annual urban population growth rate of 4.8 percent is too high
for the available resources.
</P>
<P>
The information indicates the houses in urban areas are poor
in both quality and quantity.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city of Kampala alone, a total of 279,500 new
housing units will be required by the year 2006, a shelter
strategy report by the Ministry of Housing said.
</P>
<P>
However, only100 housing units are built per year in Kampala
under government plan, and 300 to 400 housing units are
constructed by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, most of the urban houses lack basic services. For
example, 70 percent of Kampala houses use shared toilets, 60
percent use shared bedrooms, 70 percent have no kitchens and 8.5
percent have no piped water inside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
