<HEADLINE> Jordanian, U.S. Officials Meet on Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel
Raouf al-Rawabdeh Monday held talks with visiting
U.S. Under-Secretary of Defense Walter Slocombe on the defense
need and military training of the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh, who is also defense minister, and Slocombe discussed
"army defense and training," said the official news agency Petra
without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
The talks also touched on the developments in the Middle East
peace process and Jordan's efforts to narrow the differences in
stances between Israel and its Arab neighbors, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been steadily boosting the defense muscle
of the kingdom after Amman signed a peace treaty with Israel in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has promised a package of 300 million
U.S. dollars of assistance in 1999 to prop up the defense and
social security of the kingdom, and is trying to get the Congress
to endorse the package.
</P>
<P>
Washington has provided hundreds of millions of dollars' worth
of sophisticated weapons to Jordan in recent years, including F-16
fighter planes, tanks and armored vehicles, anti-tank rockets,
night vision and border monitoring equipments.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton viewed Jordan as an ally in the
Arab world, and the increased U.S. assistances are apparently
aimed at rewarding Jordan as a peace broker in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
