<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, Myanmar Likely to Sign Trade Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar on Monday agreed in
principle to sign counter trade and coastal shipping agreements
with Bangladesh to enhance trade between the two neighboring
countries, the official BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The proposed coastal shipping agreement would facilitate plying
of small vessels between Cox's Bazar-Chittagong in southeastern
Bangladesh and Sittwe in Myanmar to reduce smuggling and increase
government revenue, the BSS said.
</P>
<P>
During talks here with his Bangladeshi counterpart Tofail Ahmed
on Monday, visiting Myanmar Commerce Minister Major General Kyaw
Than expressed his country's willingness to open a new air route
and another border point.
</P>
<P>
Kyaw Than, who arrived here Sunday leading a six-member
delegation on a four-day official visit, agreed in principle to
operate private sector airlines on the Chittagong-Cox's
Bazar-Sittwe route and open new border trade point between Meikwee
of Myanmar and Bandarban of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar also agreed in principle on increasing stay time of
Bangladeshi businessmen in Sittwe to seven days from the present
72 hours.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to set up pulp mills in Myanmar in joint
venture and discussed the possibilities of setting up a cement
factory along the border using limestone from Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with members of the Federation of Bangladesh
Chambers of Commerce and Industries Monday afternoon, the Myanmar
minister hoped the existing geographical proximity of the two
countries would help promote bilateral trade, economic relations
and technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to assure you that it is my ardent desire to further
enhance our mutual interests and find all possible ways and means
for the exchange of experience and technical cooperation for
mutual benefit," he said.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between the two countries is negligible and
unstable despite huge trade potentials between the two countries,
according to BFCCI President Awal Mintoo.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of bilateral trade between the two countries
stood at 10 million U.S. dollars in fiscal 1997-98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
