<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Conservatives Promise Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition Conservative
leader William Hague Monday promised all taxpayers they would be
paying less within five years of a Tory government.
</P>
<P>
He made the pledge as one of five guarantees to voters on the
first day of the party's annual conference in Blackpool.
</P>
<P>
Other key Tory ideas are handing powers over the running of
schools to parents, forcing the unemployed to take any job on
offer and guaranteed waiting times for patients.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling the Conservatives' 43-page policy document, the "
Common Sense Revolution," Hague boasted it would provide a "step
change in the opposition to this arrogant and unresponsive
government."
</P>
<P>
The 60 policies detailed in the glossy document would be backed
by "guarantees of delivery that can't be broken," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The tax assurance is that we will take a smaller amount at the
end of the next parliament as a proportion of national income," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Tories would also use the tax system to promote marriage,
which Hague called "the cornerstone of a strong society".
</P>
<P>
While Hague stressed he was not setting out a full manifesto
for the next election, he insisted he was offering a valid
alternative to the British people.
</P>
<P>
He defined his program as giving power back to the people.
</P>
<P>
Another guarantee from Hague was that everybody who is able to
work would be forced to take a job by the Tories.
</P>
<P>
On Europe, the Conservative leader said he would keep the pound.
</P>
<P>
"When the Conservative Party wins the next election, the
attempt to bundle the country into the European single currency
will stop and we will not abolish the pound," he said, to cheers
and loud applause from party members at the back of the hall.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative leader also insisted the new policies
reflected the true aspirations of UK voters.
</P>
<P>
But opinion polls still make grim reading for Britain's main
opposition party. Two new polls on Monday showed it still
trailing heavily behind the ruling Labor Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
