<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Yet to Decide on CTBT Meeting Participation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- India has not yet made up its
mind on whether to participate in the two-day United Nations
Conference on Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) beginning in
Vienna on Wednesday, a government official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The matter is being examined," a spokesman of the External
Affairs Ministry told the press, adding that no decision had yet
been taken in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether New Delhi had been invited for the function, he
said that India had been informed in New York that "although
participation in this conference is for the ratifying states and
signatory states are present as observers, non-signatory states
may also be present".
</P>
<P>
Quoting External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh's speech at the
U.N. General Assembly in New York on September 22, the spokesman
said India was engaged in discussions on a range of issues
including CTBT and that they would be resumed by the new
government which will be formed this month.
</P>
<P>
He said that India remained ready to bring these discussions to
a successful conclusion.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally this requires the creation of a positive environment
as we work towards creating the widest possible consensus
domestically. We also expect that other countries shall adhere to
this treaty without any conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
CTBT has so far been signed by 154 countries and ratified by
only 23 countries while it needs to be ratified by 44 nuclear
capable countries for entry into force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
