<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People Development Vital to Singapore: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's New President S.
Nathan Monday said people development is vital to achieve
Singapore's vision for next millennium and the key requirement to
build his country's brighter future is "to develop our people and
strengthen our social bonds."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of the Second Session of the Ninth
Parliament of Singapore, Nathan said, "People will be the major
focus of my government's policy."
</P>
<P>
The president promised his government will create more
opportunities and space for citizens to develop to their full
potential, to get Singaporeans to play a full part in shaping his
country's future and to make everyone has a part to play in
building Singapore and has a share in its success.
</P>
<P>
Nathan said the government will refocus the education system to
prepare the next generation for a knowledge-based economy, to
develop a national system for life learning and continue to
attract foreign talent so as to make Singapore "a center of
opportunity, a global hub where people, idea and capital come
together to spark still more new ideas and opportunities."
</P>
<P>
Noting that "what really makes Singapore tick, and makes all
the other hardware and software work is our Heartware", the
president said his government will implement programs to
strengthen that Heartware of Singapore with a view to developing
social cohesion and strengthening active citizenship.
</P>
<P>
Drawing attention to the increasing aging population in
Singapore and emphasizing the need to maintain social cohesion
between the young and old, Nathan said his government will
encourage strong extended families and to maintain and reinforce
the role of the family which is the first line of care for its
older members and primary avenue for the young to support the old
and for transmitting values from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
"We want citizens to plan for old age, stay healthy, active,
secure and continue to contribute to society," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also said his government will care for the less
successful and look after the less fortunate in the society.
</P>
<P>
The government will develop a Singaporean model of a local
community social safety net that renders help where it is needed
but does not undermine incentives for people to be self-reliant
and to strive to uplift themselves, he added.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, Nathan said Singapore has to respond creatively
to the challenges of globalization and the knowledge-based economy
and "Globalization must not weaken the sense of mutual obligation
between us, between the more and less successful."
</P>
<P>
Nathan was sworn in as Singapore's sixth president on September
1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
