<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Jets Take Part in Cyprus' Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Four Greek jets on Monday took
part in Cyprus' National Guard annual military exercises
code-named "Nikiforos '99", the Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Two A-7 Consair bombers of the Greek air force participated in
one of the phases of the six-day exercises, which started last
Saturday, in Nicosia district while two F-16s took part in another
phase in the southwestern Paphos district.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' Defense Minister Socrates Hasikos watched the exercise
in Nicosia district accompanied by National Guard Commander,
Lieutenant-General Demetrios Demou.
</P>
<P>
Hasikos noted Greece's presence in the Cyprus' military
manoeuvres in a statement, stressing the "excellent" cooperation
between the military commands of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece reached an agreement in November 1993 that
Greece will offers Cyprus land, sea and air cover in the event of
fresh Turkish attacks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The exercises aim to test the Cypriot military's preparedness
and to train soldiers under realistic conditions, CNA said. All
branches of Cyprus' armed forces, both active and reserve, are
involved in the day and night-time manoeuvres.
</P>
<P>
The date of the exercises was brought forward this year in
order for Nikiforos not to interfere with talks on the Cyprus
issue which had been anticipated before the end of October.
</P>
<P>
The manoeuvres are usually carried out in late October or
early November. Cyprus' Defense Ministry said the decision to put
the exercises forward had been taken by Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides and Greek Premier Costas Simitis at their September
meeting in Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
