<HEADLINE> U.N. Council to Meet On Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council is scheduled to meet on Iraq Monday morning and
Iraq's oil export is expected to top the Council's agenda.
</P>
<P>
Under the "oil for food" deal with the United Nations, Iraq is
allowed to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six
months as to ease the humanitarian situation in the country and
the Security Council decided to raise the amount to 5.2 billion
early last year due to the deteriorating humanitarian crisis in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest report from the United Nations, Iraq is
likely to export 7 billion dollars worth of oil in the current
phase which will expire in November.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has been in an impasse on Iraq since the
U.S.-led military strikes against Iraq last December. It members
have been sharply divided over U.N. sanctions against Iraq and
the new weapons inspection mechanism for Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
