<HEADLINE> General Assembly Opens Plenary Session on Older Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The 54th General Assembly
(GA) session Monday began a two-day meeting on the older persons,
which is part of activity to mark the International Year of Older
Persons.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of some 64 delegations and eight
non-governmental organization (NGO) are expected to take the floor
at the plenary session to consider the follow-up of the
International Year of Older Persons, GA spokesperson Shirley
Brownell told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the General Assembly proclaimed 1999 as the
International Year of Older Persons, whose objective is to promote
the United Nations Principles for Older Persons.
</P>
<P>
"It is fitting for the last year of the millennium to be the
International Year of Older Persons, with the theme `towards a
society for all ages' -- a society that does not caricature older
persons as pensioners, but sees them as both agents and
beneficiaries of development," U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
has said.
</P>
<P>
Opening the plenary session, the GA president, Theo-Ben Gurirab
of Namibia, said, "It is encouraging to see that in the course of
this International Year, focal points have been established in
more than 100 Member States."
</P>
<P>
"This clearly indicates that more and more nations are
recognizing a significant increase in the population of their
older citizens who are now living longer," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Deputy Secretary-General Louise Frechette told the plenary
session, "Throughout the year, 99 national committees and
innumerable other actors from all sectors -- governments,
non-governmental organizations, academic institutions and the
corporate world, not to mention the U.N. family -- convened
conferences, organized campaigns, launched studies, held cultural
events and created Internet pages.
</P>
<P>
They are "all in pursuit of one goal: highlighting the issue of
ageing and raising awareness of the implications of the
demographic revolution for individuals and societies all over the
world," she said.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly is expected to adopt a resolution at the
end of the plenary meeting, which is to conclude Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
