<HEADLINE> GCC Members Urged to Increase Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) states must work towards greater military cooperation,
stressed a senior military leader of the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to put an end to the problems in the way of
our military cooperation through joint training and exchange of
expertise in various fields, including armaments," said Sheikh
Mohammed Bin Zayed Al-Nahyan, chief of staff of the UAE Armed
Forces.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohammed, who was presiding over the 17th meeting of the
GCC chiefs of staff which opened here Monday, also stressed the
need for more government support to increase military capabilities
and to build a unified air defense system.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abu Dhabi Crown Prince and Deputy Supreme Commander
of the UAE Armed Forces Sheikh Khalifa Bin Zayed Al-Nahyan, when
receiving the chiefs of staff, reiterated the need to enhance
military cooperation between the GCC countries to attain stability
in the region.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the two-day meeting will produce
positive results in the development of defense capabilities and
the implementation of joint projects.
</P>
<P>
The six GCC countries, namely the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Oman, Qatar and Bahrain, are all represented in their joint
Peninsula Shield force, created in 1986 and with about 4,000
troops based at Hafr El Baten in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, 12 frigates from the GCC countries started
joint naval exercises in Qatari waters.
</P>
<P>
Officials stressed that the exercises, to last until October
15, were not aimed at any particular country and were not related
to the dispute between the UAE and Iran over the sovereignty of
the islands of Abu Musa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs, currently
occupied by Tehran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
