<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, October 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban Tuesday warned
Tajikistan not to "play with fire" by supporting Afghan opposition,
threatening "grave consequences."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the religious militia's foreign ministry
accused Tajikistan of allowing the anti-Taliban alliance led by
Tajik ethnic Ahmad Shah Masood to use Tajik territory for supply
routes to their supporters.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Taliban groups use Tajikistan's Kolyab airbase close to
the Afghan border while Tajik ships carry military supplies to
Masood through a newly-built crossing point on the Oxus river into
the opposition base in Takhar province, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan, once again stressing its
desire of having friendly relations with all countries,
particularly the neighbors, seriously warns the Dushanbe regime
rulers that they will face grave consequences of playing with this
fire," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have controlled over 80 percent of the territory of
Afghanistan during their five-year-long war against the opposition
alliance, but the regime of Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan it
established has been recognized only by three Islamic countries
including Saudi Arabia, Pakistan and UAE.
</P>
<P>
At the U.N. General Assembly last week, Tajikistan urged the
world body to consider imposing sanctions against those, in a
direct reference to the Taliban, who "violate the resolutions of
the Security Council and the General Assembly." (Afghanistan-
Taliban-Tajikistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Monday urged
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad to move the Israeli-Syrian peace
process forward.
</P>
<P>
"The door of opportunity is opened today and let us make
painful decisions to solve the problems between Israel and Syria,"
Barak said in his policy address to the Knesset (parliament) which
opened its winter session after a two-month summer recession. (
Israel-Syria-Barak)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council is
scheduled to meet on Iraq Monday morning and Iraq's oil export is
expected to top the Council's agenda.
</P>
<P>
Under the "oil for food" deal with the United Nations, Iraq is
allowed to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six
months as to ease the humanitarian situation in the country and
the Security Council decided to raise the amount to 5.2 billion
early last year due to the deteriorating humanitarian crisis in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest report from the United Nations, Iraq is
likely to export 7 billion dollars worth of oil in the current
phase which will expire in November.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has been in an impasse on Iraq since the U.
S.-led military strikes against Iraq last December. It members
have been sharply divided over U.N. sanctions against Iraq and the
new weapons inspection mechanism for Iraq. (Iraq-UN-Council)
</P>
</TEXT>
