<HEADLINE> Finnish President to Visit Lebanon on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari will make a lightning visit to Beirut on Wednesday as
part of his Middle East peace-making endeavor, the state-run
National News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
During his two-hour stay in Beirut, the president will hold
talks with his Lebanese counterpart Emile Lahoud to sound out
views of Middle East adversaries and speak about the European
Union (EU) aspirations to play an active role in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
European diplomatic sources said Ahtisaari may be carrying new
ideas to jumpstart talks on the Syrian-Lebanese peace track which
has been stalled for three and a half years.
</P>
<P>
His visit is also meant to relay a message to the United
States, a co-sponsor of the peace process, that is Europe has a
complementary political role in the peace talks which the
U.S. should not ignore, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari's tour comes when some Arab leaders, notably those
of Syria and Lebanon, are calling for a more active European role
in the talks to offset the U.S. bias in favor of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari, accompanied by Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen and
EU peace envoy Miguel Angel Moratinos, will also visit the Gaza
strip and Israel after a trip to Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Finland currently holds the half-yearly rotating presidency of
the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
