<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.2 Mln EU Citizens Protest Live Animal Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1.2 million European
Union (EU) citizens have presented their signatures for a protest
action against subsidies of live animal transport which was held
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The signatures were shredded openly to demonstrate the
"helpless of the EU citizens." The Taxpayers Association of Europe
(TAE), organizer of the event, said in a statement that the
"merciless business, which threatens animals as mere products, is
continuing."
</P>
<P>
Neither the EU regulation on the protection of animals during
transport, which has been in force for five years, nor the
European-wide campaigns for the abolition of the EU-subsidies for
the export of living cattle could stop "the cruel lorry and ship
transport to as far as North Africa and the Middle East, the TAE
said.
</P>
<P>
The World Day of Animal Welfare fell on Monday, so they
launched the protest action in front of the building of EU
Commissioner of Agriculture Franz Fischler, sources from the TAE's
Brussels office said.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the 1.2 million signatures had been handed over as a
petition to the EU commissioner last year. The TAE said that
despite hopeful first signs within the bounds of the EU's Agenda
2000 and a resolution of the European Parliament, the appalling
suffering of transported animals continued as before.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, "the EU Commission even raised the
subsidies for life animal exports by 8 percent," the TAE said.
</P>
<P>
The taxpayers' group also used many official facts and figures
to support what they have been arguing. The taxpayer
representatives said they just want to prove that the existing EU
legal regulations are insufficient and offer too many loopholes to
the traders and transport companies.
</P>
<P>
"Only cuts in subsidies for the export of living animals and an
amendment of the EU Directive, which would limit the
transportation time of `slaughter animal' to four hours, could
achieve a noticeable improvement and could finally stop this waste
of tax money," the TAE added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
