<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Accuses NGOs of Backing  Anti-Gov. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Fredrick
Chiluba has delivered a scathing attack on non-governmental
organizations (NGOs) for supporting dubious publications which
denigrate Africans, Zimbabwe News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Sunday night during the question and answer session
by African leaders and media editors at the Southern Africa
International Dialogue (SAID) being held in Victoria Fall,
Zimbabwe, Chiluba said the NGOs were abandoning their role in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The NGOs seem to have interests in African issues when things
go wrong, they support dubious publications which seek to disturb
our peace through their writings. Obviously this is not their
role," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was surprising that some of the small publications
which could not even produce a balance sheet and with a very
limited number of readers were still able to survive despite
economic hardships facing most African countries.
</P>
<P>
He said it was also clear from the editorials in the
publications that the editors were not interested in development
issues but to serve the interests of the NGOs.
</P>
<P>
He said the traditional role of NGOs has been lost. They have
become pressure groups in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Henry Muradzikwa, editor-in-chief of the Zimbabwe News Agency,
said the only solution was for the African governments to enact
laws that governed the operations of the NGOs.
</P>
<P>
The four-day SAID meeting, attended by most Southern African
leaders and their smart partners from Ghana, Kenya, Uganda and
Malaysia, will focus on building partnerships to cooperate in
economic, social and political issues.
</P>
<P>
There are also representatives from Europe, Latin America and
the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
