<HEADLINE> Rebel Irish Guerrillas Plan London Raid: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Renegade Irish republican
guerrillas are planning to attack the centerpiece of Britain's
celebrations for the year 2000, the Millennium Dome in London, the
Times newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, quoting unidentified sources in the Irish
Republic's police special branch, said the renegades came from the
Real IRA guerrilla group and that they were plotting a campaign
aimed at high-profile landmarks in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republic police said they have received information
that attacks are likely to be mounted around the new year to
coincide with any millennium bug computer problems.
</P>
<P>
The Real IRA was responsible for Northern Ireland's single
biggest atrocity, the 1998 bombing of the town of Omagh which
killed 29 people.
</P>
<P>
Soon afterwards, the Real IRA joined mainstream guerrilla
groups, such as the Irish Republican Army (IRA) and its Protestant,
pro-British "Loyalist" foes, in observing a ceasefire as part of
Northern Ireland's shaky peace process.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted one officer as saying that a bomb spectacular
in England would have a two-edged effect -- it would upset the
delicate peace talks in Northern Ireland and boost recruitment
among younger republicans.
</P>
<P>
Irish Republic police on Friday arrested six people in a pre-
emptive move to avert an attack by dissident republicans.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's peace process has been stalled for months by
wrangling between politicians from the Protestant majority and
Catholic minority over the issue of guerrilla disarmament.
</P>
</TEXT>
