<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Foreign Exchange Reserves Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's foreign exchange
reserves fell from 7.2 billion U.S. dollars in December last year
to 5.009 billion U.S. dollars in June this year.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by a review of economy for the first half of
this year issued by the Manufacturers Association of Nigeria
(MAN), the Daily Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The association noted that the fall in external reserves
resulted from activities in the Autonomous Foreign Exchange Market
which came under pressure from a massive injection of liquidity.
</P>
<P>
However, the remarkable price increase of oil which is
Nigeria's major earner of foreign exchange has a positive impact
on its foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
The oil price has climbed from 10.42 U.S. dollars per barrel in
February this year to 15 U.S. dollars in the past three months,
according to the review.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's oil production and export for the first half of this
year were lower than that of the same period of 1998, but "this
drop has been compensated by the oil price increase".
</P>
<P>
For now, "the situation is critical which called for measures
to enhance the nation's non-oil exports, which from all
indicat of improvement in the capital market
with foreign investment inflow putting at 12 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The increase of foreign investment was a reflection of the
increasing confidence of foreign investors in the economy, the
review noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
