<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Fund for Macao SAR Tops 1.2 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The land fund of the future Macao
Special Administrative Region (SAR) has increased to 9.5 billion
patacas (about 1.2 billion U.S. dollars), a Chinese official said.
</P>
<P>
The land fund may exceed 10 billion patacas (1.25 billion U.S.
dollars) at the end of the year if the current Portuguese Macao
government effectively demands the payment of land-using fees,
Yang Runzhen, chief representative of the Chinese side of the Sino-
Portuguese Land Group, said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
The fund comes from land-leasing approved by the Portuguese
Macao government with the deduction of land development cost. The
total income is shared evenly by the current Macao government and
the future Macao SAR government.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Portuguese Land Group was established in January of
1988 and will end its work on December 19 this year. The Chinese
side of the group is entrusted to manage the fund on behalf of the
future Macao SAR government.
</P>
<P>
"In the management of the land fund, the Chinese side follows
the principle of stability and low risk, and attempts to obtain
greater profits from the fund," Yang Runzhen said.
</P>
<P>
A major part of the fund managed by the Chinese side is
deposited in banks or used to buy bonds which are rather safe. In
1998, the average profit rate of the fund reached a record of 8.41
percent despite the Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The Macao SAR government will be set up in less than three
months. Yang Runzhen said that she will find a proper time to talk
about the transfer of the land fund with the chief executive-
designate of the SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
