<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Curb Insurance Irregularities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has vowed to take
measures against irregularities in the insurance sector by
conducting regular checks.
</P>
<P>
"From now on there will be regular onsite inspections at your
offices. Anybody found not complying with the provisions of the
insurance law will not be tolerated," said the Commissioner of
Insurance Crony Kasamala.
</P>
<P>
Kasamala gave this warning while attending a dinner party
hosted by Imperial Insurance Company Ltd. on Friday night in Dar
es Salaam, The Guardian newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The inspections are also aimed at detecting early signals of
mismanagement in the companies to safeguard premiums of
policyholders, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official urged all insurance brokers in the country to
cooperate with the Commission of Insurance in detecting ailing
insurers, and called on them to immediately report to the
commission all delays in settlement of claims, commission payment
or other unsatisfactory practices.
</P>
<P>
He warned insurers not to bend professional ethics in favor of
the interest of its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
So far, Tanzania has licensed 11 insurance companies, 157
agents and 24 brokers since the industry was liberalized last
year, ending the monopoly of the State Insurance Brokers Limited.
</P>
<P>
In an annual insurance meeting last month, President of the
Insurance Institute of Tanzania Inayat Manji said that settlement
of claims, rate undercutting and lack of professional training are
some of the bottlenecks in the insurance sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
