<HEADLINE> Iraqi Deputy PM Ends Visit to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq
Aziz return home Monday after a brief and secret visit to Amman
ahead of a U.S. trip by Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Aziz left Amman early Monday morning after overnight talks
with Jordanian officials, including Prime Minister Abdul Abdel
Raouf al-Rawabdeh and Foreign Minister Abdel-Ilah al-Khatib on
bilateral ties and regional issues, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources remained tight-lipped over the details of the
talks, and it is not immediately clear whether Aziz's surprise
visit is connected with Abdullah`s imminent U.S. visit.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah is expected to visit U.S. on Friday and will meet
President Bill Clinton on October 12 on the Mideast peace process,
bilateral ties and the nine-year-old U.N. sanctions on Iraq, which
was imposed on Baghdad following its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was once isolated by Arab countries for its sympathy
with Iraq during the Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Jordan normalized its ties with Kuwait earlier this year after
nine years of strains, but it heavily depends on Baghdad for crude
oil. It imports some 75,000 barrels of oil from Iraq a day.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government has on many occasions appealed for
lifting the crippling sanctions to end the sufferings of the Iraqi
people.
</P>
<P>
Al-Rawabdeh said his government based its foreign policies on
keeping friendly relations with all countries, and will not
improve its ties with one country at the expense of another.
</P>
</TEXT>
