<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Profits Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- European champions Manchester
United might have had a rare bad day on the pitch yesterday,
losing 5-0 to Chelsea, but the Treble winners last season helped
the company to better than expected full-year results, achieving
sales of more than 100 million pounds for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The group reported operating profits of 32.3m in the year to
the end of July, compared to 27m last year, and ahead of analysts'
expectations of 30-31m.
</P>
<P>
The share dividend from the world's richest football club was
raised by 5.9% - to 1.25p from 1.18p.
</P>
<P>
Player wages continued to grow, with costs jumping by 7.7m,
including 3.5m paid out in bonuses to team members for winning the
FA Cup, Premiership and European Champions Cup.
</P>
<P>
After player trading costs, and 1.8m spent on professional
advisers' fees during BSkyB's abortive takeover attempt, pre-tax
profits were down from 27.8m to 22.4m.
</P>
<P>
Accounting changes mean player transfer costs take a bigger
chunk from profits than before. This "player amortisation charge"
came to 10.2m - up 5.5m on last year.
</P>
<P>
Turnover increased 26% to 110.7m, from 87.9m, following a
higher number of home games and improved TV and sponsorship
revenues.
</P>
<P>
These helped offset a reduction in merchandising revenue, but
the group says it is confident about future merchandising
opportunities overseas, particularly in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Merchandising sales fell 10% to 21.6m, mainly due to a change
in replica kit supply arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The group - which has also launched its TV channel, MUTV,
alongside Granada and BSkyB - has admitted that subscriptions have
been lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United said the three parties were addressing this.
It says it has also launched a website - www.manutd.com.
</P>
<P>
The club's stadium expansion, costing 30m, is progressing well,
said chairman Sir Roland Smith. The expansion will provide another
6,200 East Stand seats in March next year.
</P>
<P>
Roland also said an additional 6,200 West Stand seats would be
available in August 2000 and that Old Trafford would then have a
capacity of 67,400 - a year ahead of schedule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
