<HEADLINE> Kenya Disputes With U.N. over Peace-keeping Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Whether Kenya will participate
in the United Nations peace-keeping force in East Timor has come
into spotlight following a dispute over 20 million U.S. dollars
owed to the African country by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
The appeal to Kenya to contribute troops to the U.N. operation
was presented by Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas two weeks
ago, the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Alatas reportedly told Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana in
New York that Indonesia would prefer a peace-keeping force
comprising substantial number of Asian and African countries.
</P>
<P>
A claim of 20 million U.S. dollars by Kenya for its
contribution to U.N. peacekeeping missions has been outstanding
since 1996, but the U.N. said that it owed Kenya only 4.3 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Godana said that Kenya could participate in the East Timor
mission if funds were provided by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has sent a battalion to the U.N. peace-keeping operation
in Sierra Leone and a 20-man police contingent to Kosovo. 
</P>
