<HEADLINE> Record-Seeking Copter to Arrive in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A single-engine British
helicopter on a record-breaking journey from Britain to Australia
is due to arrive here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tim Gilbert and Martin Rutty, the two pilots, will stay here
for two days while their Robinson R44 helicopter undergoes an
overhaul, the Gulf News daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two Britons, who started their epic journey in Cambridge,
England, on September 24, plan to fly 22,400 kilometers and 150
hours in the air before arriving in their destination --
Australia's Sydney. The whole journey is expected to take six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Their route, covering North Africa, the Gulf, the Indian
subcontinent and Southeast Asia, will take them to 22 countries
with 51 fuel stops.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Cambridge-Sydney journey is being
staged to raise funds for the international charity organization
SOS Children's Village, which is celebrating its 50th anniversary
this year.
</P>
<P>
Proceeds from the journey will be used to help the SOS
Children's Village in Ibid, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The world record attempt will also mark the 80th anniversary
of the first long distance flight from Britain to Sydney by the
Australian Smith brothers in a Vickers-Vimy biplane, following
the same route, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
