<HEADLINE> Myanmar Concerned Over Future Safety of Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has expressed concern
over the future safety and security of its representatives and
diplomatic premises abroad following the peaceful ending on last
Saturday of the seizure of its embassy in Bangkok and the taking
of hostages by Myanmar armed men.
</P>
<P>
"Although this ordeal has been over this time, the government
of Myanmar, together with the world community, is deeply
concerned with the future safety and security of their
representatives and diplomatic premises in foreign countries,"
said a government statement released here Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
"Upon the pretext of the precedent, other radical or even
non-radical groups may get the wrong message that these kinds of
terrorists and criminal activities can be conveniently carried out
under the banner of freedom, democracy and human rights," the
government Information Sheet said.
</P>
<P>
It complained that a number of camps along the Thai-Myanmar
border have become breeding ground of dissident terrorists for
armed violence and sanctuaries for radicals.
</P>
<P>
"These individuals or groups have been staging acts of violence
and terrorism for many decades along the Thai-Myanmar border and
also infiltrating into Myanmar proper to terrorize the innocent
people by their continuous attempts and to destabilize peace and
tranquillity," the Information Sheet charged.
</P>
<P>
The statement expressed regret that the recent incident of the
embassy take-over in Bangkok by these terrorist groups seems to
indicate that foreign diplomats with their families and embassy
premises are now very much vulnerable to acts of violence and
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Five armed men with AK47 rifles, who are all Myanmar students
living in Thailand, stormed the Myanmar embassy in Bangkok last
Friday and held the embassy staff and their families together with
a number of foreigners who came for visa application.
</P>
<P>
The incident ended peacefully last Saturday afternoon with 34
hostages freed and the gunmen leaving the embassy compound by
minibus provided by the Thai authorities after negotiation
between them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
