<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturing Fault Caused Apache Crash in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- An investigation indicated
that a manufacturing fault caused the fatal crash of a U.S.-made
Israeli air force Apache helicopter in June this year, the Israeli
army said Monday.
</P>
<P>
An Apache attack helicopter, manufactured by the American
Boeing Company, crashed in southern Israel on June 1 while
attempting an emergency landing. The flight mechanic was killed
and the pilot injured.
</P>
<P>
A faulty part in the helicopter's hydraulic system caused the
crash, said the army in a inquiry. Also, the helicopter's
emergency backup system did not work as designed, the inquiry
added.
</P>
<P>
After the hydraulic system failed, the pilot tried to execute
an emergency landing, but the rotors seized and the helicopter
crashed. The Israeli army blamed the manufacturer for the defects.
</P>
<P>
There have been previous mishaps involving Apache helicopters
in Israel, but the cause was not determined until now.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry showed that the hydraulic part had worn out
much faster than the manufacturer expected. The findings were
passed on to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
The Apache helicopter, in service in the U.S. army since
1984, is meant to knock out enemy tanks. It carries anti-tank
missiles and a machine gun and is capable of operating in
adverse weather conditions and at night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
