<HEADLINE> Wanted Palestinian Allowed to Cross Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel Monday allowed
Palestinian police chief Ghazi Jabali, who is wanted for his
alleged role in an attack, to cross Israel from Gaza to the West
Bank to attend his father's funeral.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak granted Jabali the permission to
enter the West Bank city of Ramallah for the funeral, Barak's
office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Israel issued an arrest warrant against Jabali two years ago
for his alleged involvement in the planning of an attack against a
Jewish settlement near the West Bank city of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Three Palestinian police officers arrested by Israel allegedly
on their way to carry out the attack were held for a year without
trial and then released.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Israel had revoked Jabali's VIP pass to cross Israeli
territories without security checks and demanded his
extradition. The Palestinian side denied the charges against
Jabali and refused to hand him over to Israel, which later
dropped its extradition demand.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security sources said that Jabali would travel in
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's helicopter to Ramallah and
would return to Gaza within four hours.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a group of Israeli settlers gathered at the Erez
Checkpoint between the Gaza Strip and Israel to protest against
Jabali's travel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
