<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel: Some Progress in Safe Passage Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Palestinian
negotiators reported some progress in talks here Sunday night, in
efforts to resolve their differences that has delayed the opening
of the safe passage between the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The two sides were close to agreement on the distribution of
magnetic cards, but differences still remain over Israel's demand
of having the right to arrest suspected Palestinians on the
passage, and the talks will continue Monday evening, according to
a senior official of the Public Security Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm El Sheikh Memorandum signed last month, the
passage linking Gaza and the West Bank city of Hebron was to have
opened on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But this was postponed after hours of talks Saturday night
failed to resolve two disagreements over who should issue the
magnetic cards to the Palestinians and Israel's demand to have
the right to arrest Palestinians suspected of security offenses.
</P>
<P>
The level of talks was stepped up Sunday night at the request
of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who reportedly spoke on the
telephone with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak earlier Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat, Gaza Preventive Security
Chief Mohammed Dahlan and Palestinian cabinet Minister of Civil
Affairs Jamil Tarifi were among the Palestinian delegation team.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli team was led by Public Security Minister Shlomo
Ben-Ami.
</P>
<P>
After several hours of talks Sunday night, both sides split up
to discuss proposals raised in the talks. The main bone of
contention appeared to be which side would issue the cards. The
Palestinians proposed a compromise of setting up a joint office
to issue the cards, but the Israeli side expressed concern that
this method could be used to forge cards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
