<HEADLINE> WHO Launches Polio Immunization Campaign in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
launched a nationwide immunization campaign in Iraq Monday to
protect children under five from a polio outbreak there.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will be conducted in two rounds, from October 4 to
6 and from November 8 to 10, targeting 3.5 million Iraqi children.
Two more rounds will follow in next spring, WHO told the press
here.
</P>
<P>
"It is crucial to the global eradication effort to control the
outbreak in Iraq, and to prevent polio from spreading into
neighboring polio-free countries," said Dr. Harry Hull of the WHO
Expanded Program on Immunization.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO, declining routine immunization coverage in
many areas as well as insufficient National Immunization Day
coverage in southern and central governorates, especially among
high-risk populations, contribute to the eruption of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Since May, 16 cases of paralytic poliomyelitis in nine out of
18 Iraq governorates have been confirmed, said WHO. Another 19
cases are being investigated.
</P>
<P>
WHO warned that widespread transmission of wild poliovirus in
Iraq is posing a threat to the goal of eradicating polio by the
end of 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
