<HEADLINE> Two Bombs Explode in Pak, No Casualty Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Two explosive devices went off
Monday morning in Pakistan's southern province of Sindh, but no
casualty was reported.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Hyderabad, a central Sindh town, said that the two
explosive devices went off consecutively in the jurisdiction of
cantonment police station in the town.
</P>
<P>
The first device exploded near Hyderabad Circuit Bench of Sindh
High Court at about 10:05 a.m. The big bang of the device
up-rooted an electric pole and jolted the surrounding buildings.
</P>
<P>
Another bomb went off at the boundary wall of Barrage Colony
near Pathan Colony of the National High way at about 10:10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy Commissioner of Hyderabad, Raashid Bashir Mazari,
was quoted by Associated Press of Pakistan as saying that the
bombs were planted beneath bushes at both instances and were of
mild intensity.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was an act of terrorism aimed to create scare
among the citizens. Earlier, he said, three explosive devices,
planted near Court building, Post Office and Qasim Chowck
respectively were detected and defused by the bomb disposal squad.
</P>
<P>
Security has been beefed up in the city to thwart nefarious
designs of anti-social elements adding that thorough checking of
suspected persons and vehicles is being carried out, according to
Mazari. 
</P>
</TEXT>
