<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Israel Lebanese Militia Wants not to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- senior South Lebanese Army
(SLA) commanders have requested Israel to take steps to ensure the
SLA not be dismantled after Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon,
local daily Haaretz reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
the request showed that the SLA wants Israel to guarantee that
the SLA commanders and their troops are not abandoned after its
pullout.
</P>
<P>
The report added that the SLA's senior command is interested in
exploring the possibility of its being integrated into the
Lebanon's armed forces as an intact brigade that would be based in
southern Lebanon. They told Israel that such a step would be
beneficial to enhancing regional security on both sides of the
border.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli Defense Ministry sources, the late Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin explored such a possibility, but did
not pursue it after it became clear that it was unlikely to
work.
</P>
<P>
The SLA has about 2,500 personnel and many of them are former
members of Lebanese armed forces. Although they have continued to
receive their Lebanese pensions, many of them have been
court-martialed in abstentia and sentenced to long prison terms
and even death. Their main concern till now has been to ensure
that once the security zone returns to Lebanese control, their
sentences would be annulled by some form of amnesty or pardon.
</P>
<P>
SLA is a Lebanese military faction supporting Israel's
occupation in the security zone in south Lebanon, which was set up
by Israel in 1985 for self-claimed purpose of protecting Israel's
northern security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
