<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Agrees to Drop DFLP From Terror List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. has agreed to remove
the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP) from
its terror list now it no longer opposes the Mideast peace
process, a senior Palestinian official confirmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
During his recent visit to Washington, Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat has requested the U.S. authorities to scrape the
DFLP from its terror list, the unnamed official said in the West
Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. move reportedly came after DFLP's leadership dropped
their policy of armed struggle and its opposition to the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. DFLP has agreed to join the
final-status talks and its leader Nayef Hawatmeh has also been
seeking Israeli permission to enter the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
The DFLP was one of several Palestinian factions appearing on
the U.S. State Department's terrorist list.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the official added, that the Palestinian National
Authority has also submitted a request to the U.S. authorities to
ask for the drop of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine (PFLP), another Syria-based radical Palestinian faction,
from the list.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Israel allowed Mustafa Zibri, PFLP's No. 2, to
return to the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli defense officials said Sunday night that the
U.S. decision would have no bearing on Israel's view of the DFLP,
adding that the faction's status would only be changed at the
recommendation of intelligence and security bodies after
considering their actions.
</P>
<P>
But Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh said Sunday that
Israel has to turn a new leaf, indicating that the Israeli
government may allow Hawatmeh's return to the Palestinian-controlled
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
