<DOCNO> XIE19991004.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Supports 16-Team Premier League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- European champions Manchester
United supported the proposal of smaller premier league, deputy
chief executive Peter Kenyon said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It had been said that there was a call to cut the league from
current 20 to 16 teams.
</P>
<P>
Kenyon said United had long argued for a smaller premier league
and that the enlarged European Champions League, now a 32-team
competition, reinforced that view.
</P>
<P>
"We felt there needed to be a reduction in the numbers and that
(the enlarged Champions League) has done nothing to change our
opinion," Kenyon told reporters in a telephone briefing.
</P>
<P>
Kenyon said he believed 16 teams would be the optimum number
for the premier league. Such proposals would meet strong
resistance from the bulk of premier league teams, fearful of lost
revenue from a smaller number of fixtures and the increased risk
of relegation from the elite.
</P>
<P>
The new Champions League format means a team would have to play
17 games to win the competition this season, up from 11 under the
previous format.
</P>
<P>
United, Arsenal and Chelsea are the English teams in this
season's Champions League and their domestic performances have
tended to dip after big midweek European ties.
</P>
<P>
United were hammered 5-0 on Sunday but ironically this defeat
came at the hands of fellow Champions League contenders Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
Kenyon's words are sure to be warmly received by UEFA, European
soccer's ruling body, who have long advocated a reduction in the
size of bigger top divisions.
</P>
<P>
Spain, like England, has a top division of 20 teams and has
also come under pressure from UEFA in the past to reduce the
number.
</P>
<P>
Kenyon was speaking as United reported a 20 percent jump in
annual operating profit to 32.3 million pounds (53.4 million
dollars) on the back of its treble triumph last season.
</P>
<P>
United, regarded as the world's richest soccer club, said plans
to increase seating at its Old Trafford stadium were ahead of
schedule and that it would have a capacity of 67,400 from August
2000 -- a year earlier than planned.
</P>
<P>
The stadium in Manchester, north-west England, currently holds
some 55,000 people.
</P>
<P>
United, winners of the domestic premier league and F.A. Cup
double as well as the European Cup, said turnover jumped 26
percent to 110.7 million pounds -- the first time a club has
broken through the 100 million pound level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
