<HEADLINE> Cambodia to Open New Horizons for Disabled People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prime Minister Hun Sen said in his opening speech, "I believe
that this seminar highlights an important thesis for our Cambodian
society as a whole."
</P>
<P>
He urged the government and the whole society to encourage the
disabled people to feel they are not isolated from society or
useless to society and family.
</P>
<P>
"Based on this, the Royal Government as well as the ministries,
all institutions and NGOs should pay more attention to make the
whole society open up to the new horizons for disabled people, so
that the people with disabilities will understand that they and
the society are being together with the same benefits," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a Socio Economic Survey 1997, Cambodia has a
disabled population of 203,000, or 2.2 percent of the total
population, due to the many years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
Of this number, 33 percent resulted from diseases, 25 percent
congenital, 20 percent due to war and landmine explosion and
around 13 percent due to other accidental incident.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen demanded that "the disabled people will equally stand
at the same level as others and may challenge freely so as to make
a living possible in this free market." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
