<HEADLINE> Kenyan Media Launch War Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan media houses have pledged
to allocate more air time and space for information about AIDS in
a bid to boost public awareness on the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
Senior editors and journalists attending the two-day AIDS/HIV
Press Workshop have formed the coalition of media against AIDS to
coordinate and monitor the dissemination of information on
HIV/AIDS in the press.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, opened Sunday in the Kenyan port city of
Mombasa, is jointly organized by the United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) and the U. N. Program on AIDS (UNAIDS).
</P>
<P>
UNICEF country representative to Kenya Crispin Wilson told the
participants that journalists should play a key role in checking
the spread of the disease by disseminating facts without fear.
</P>
<P>
Meshack Ndolo, Kenya's national coordinator of the AIDS/HIV
Program, challenged the media to take a more aggressive role in
fighting the scourge by making information of the disease readily
available.
</P>
<P>
Kipserem Maritim, editor-in-chief of Kenya Broadcasting
Corporation, told the workshop that the KBC radio has lunched a
campaign against HIV/AIDS through programs in English, Kiswahili
and 19 vernacular languages countrywide.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was attended by editors and journalists from major
media including Kenya News Agency, Daily Nation, East African
Standard and Kenya Television Network.
</P>
<P>
The AIDS disease is rampant in Kenya which has recorded a toll
of more than 700,000 people since the first AIDS case found in
1984. There are estimated two million Kenyans infected with HIV
and about 500 people die of AIDS everyday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
