<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Offers 100 Million Dollars to Multinational Force in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko
Komura announced Monday that Japan will contribute 100 million U.S.
dollars to help developing countries participate in the
multinational peace-keeping force in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government made this decision after the United
Nations informally told Japan the total cost of the multinational
force would be around 220 million dollars, Komura told the press.
</P>
<P>
But the Japanese contribution "could be either increased or
decreased depending on the situation," Komura said.
</P>
<P>
The contribution will go to a U.N. trust fund, aiming to help
countries willing to join the multinational force but unable to
afford it.
</P>
<P>
Komura added Japan is ready to provide more humanitarian aid to
East Timorese refugees in line with an international emergency
appeal to be announced soon by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Japan has already contributed 2 million dollars to the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees and the World Food Program for
their operations in East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
