<HEADLINE> 115 Thai Soldiers Leave for Darwin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The second batch of 115 Thai
soldiers left here for Darwin, Australia at 11:30 a.m. Monday to
join multinational peacekeeping force in East Timor, an informed
source here confirmed.
The first batch of 33 Thai soldiers left here for Darwin on
September 17.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has decided to send 1,500 troops to East Timor. The
figure represents a slight drop from the 1,778 troops originally
planned.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai wanted
to send only as many as necessary to join the international
peacekeeping force in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Supreme Commander of the Supreme Command of the
Thai Armed Forces Mongkol Ampornpisit was quoted as saying that
Thai troops were not going to East Timor to kill or harm anyone,
but to secure communication lines, to help East Timorese in their
reconstruction work, and to restore law and order. 
</P>
