<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, October 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- Cavalese, a northern Italian ski resort, has claimed 44
billion lire (about 24 million U.S. dollars)from the government in
compensation for the cablecar tragedy that occurred at the resort
early last year.
</P>
<P>
On February 3, 1998, 20 tourists aboard a cablecar were killed
when the tail-fin of a U.S. Marine EA-6B Prowler surveillance
plane sliced the ski-lift cable above the Cermis mountain during a
ground-hugging training flight from a NATO air base in nearby
Aviano. (Italy-Cablecar Disaster-Compensation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- The largest Japanese automaker Toyota Motor Corp.
produced its 100 millionth vehicle in Japan on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Toyota is the world's third automaker to achieve domestic
production of 100 million vehicles, following two major U.S.
automakers, General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.(Japan-Toyota)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's highest Sunni Muslim authority has banned
the use of Koranic verses in songs, one day after a famous
Lebanese singer was accused of insulting Islam by quoting the
Koran in his song.
</P>
<P>
The authority said in a statement that the recitation of any
verses from the Koran, the Muslim holy book, was only permitted in
sermons, speeches, praises of God and forms of scientific studies
or instructive literature, the Daily Star reported Monday. (
Lebanon-Singer-Islam)
</P>
