<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise in Tokyo on Improved Business Sentiment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices in Tokyo rose Monday
for the third straight trading day, following the release of the
quarterly Tankan survey by the Bank of Japan (BOJ) showing
improved business confidence.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 51.15
points or 0.29 percent from last Friday's close ending at 17,763.
71.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 0.90 point or 0.06 percent to 1,515.98.
</P>
<P>
Before the stock market opened, Japan's central bank said the
diffusion index of business sentiment among major Japanese
manufacturers rose from minus 37 recorded in June to minus 22. The
index for large nonmanufacturers rose from minus 28 to minus 23.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei index opened higher, but fell back later as the
yen, boosted by the better-than-expected Tankan figures, rose
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark index turned upward shortly, as the yen turned
lower, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
At 3 p.m., the dollar was traded at 105.82-85 yen, after
falling to as low as 104.42 yen earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased from 543.54 million
shares last Friday to 434.23 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo Metal Mining was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers exceeded
gainers 657 to 568 despite the rise of the Nikkei and the TOPIX,
with 113 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
