<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Hosts Fund Managers Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A two-day institutional fund
managers conference was inaugurated here Monday by Sri Lankan
Trade Minister Kingsley Wickramaratne to attract much-needed
capital for the country's stock market.
</P>
<P>
Wickramaratne said the Colombo stock market has been plagued by
a lack of liquidity for some time due to external reasons.
</P>
<P>
The market, with about half of its trading done by foreign
funds, lost 41 percent of its value between May and September 1998
due to the effects of the East Asian crisis and the tit-for-tat
nuclear tests which forced foreign fund managers to withdraw from
South Asia countries including Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
But he was hopeful that Colombo would be a focal point for
financial activities, with its advantages in terms of technology,
accounting standards and regulatory framework ahead of neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister's prediction was endorsed by Ayaz Ebrahim, a fund
manager with the Indocam Asset Management Ltd, a Hong Kong-based
investment company with an asset of 150 billion U.S. dollars
globally.
</P>
<P>
Ebrahim told the conference that Sri Lanka would be a favorite
for fund managers as it has central depositing system,
well-established regulatory practices, good transparency and other
investors-friendly conditions.
</P>
<P>
The conference on Value vs Price, Exploring the Potential of
the Colombo Stock Market is hosted by Colombo Stock Exchange (CSE)
in association with the Securities and Exchange Commission of Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
It is attended by over 200 local fund managers and 26 foreign
counterparts from 10 countries, including Australia, China's Hong
Kong, India and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The CSE is tiny in size with a market capitalization of 1.4
billion U.S. dollars, about 10 percent of the country's gross
domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
