<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Region Urged to Formulate Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has appealed to the Southern African region to formulate
strategies to promote economic integration on an equitable basis
while guarding against the bad effects of globalization.
</P>
<P>
The host president made the call at the third Southern African
International Dialogue conference opened in Zimbabwe's Victoria
Falls Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address, Mugabe said developing countries were
less prepared to face the challenges of globalization and called
for formulating regulations or abolishing currency trading, the
daily Herald reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Currency trading and speculation have led to financial crises
in south- east Asia and a number of African countries, including
Zimbabwe over the last two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
The economic downturns triggered mainly by speculation on the
foreign currency market have been worsened by the crippling
foreign debt of developing countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen heads of State and Government and about 400 delegates
of industry, politicians from the region, the Commonwealth and
beyond are attending the conference to chart the way forward for
the region grappling with low economic growth, growing
unemployment, spiralling inflation and the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"Globalization builds strong economic cooperation and promotes
the interaction of countries to enhance economic development."
Mugabe said, adding: "It should manifest itself in greater
inter-dependence and cross- border linkages between and among the
various countries and regions of the world."
</P>
<P>
Developing countries that are ill equipped to participate
actively in a globalized economy risk being further marginalized
by other players, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The experiences of both Asia and southern and eastern Africa's
worst financial crises in the last two years, spawned by foreign
currency speculators and hedge funds, have alerted us of the
developing or emerging markets to the danger of exposing our
markets and financial systems. Indeed, we now demand serious
reform to the global financial system in order to stop or regulate
currency trading," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
This year's session is the third after the inaugural dialogue
held in Kasane, Botswana, in 1997 and the second held in
Swakopmund, Namibia, last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
