<HEADLINE> Elephants Damage Farms in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Elephants from a Kenyan national
reserve have turned the nearby farms into a mess, uprooting
fences, trees and food crops.
</P>
<P>
The farmers in Narok town of Rift Valley Province usually left
home after 7 am and returned before 6 pm to avoid being attacked
by a herd of 200 elephants,
</P>
<P>
according to Monday's Daily Nation newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The elephant menace also interrupted the order in seven primary
schools in the area.
</P>
<P>
Frightened and angry residents warned at the weekend that they
would take up arms against the elephants if the Kenya Wildlife
Service (KWS) did not tame the animals.
</P>
<P>
They complained that elephants from the Maasai Mara National
Reserve invaded the area annually and no compensation was ever
offered.
</P>
<P>
However, KWS Narok area officer Joseph Nashuu said a contingent
of rangers had been dispatched to drive off the elephants.
</P>
</TEXT>
