<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Religious Authority Bans Use Koran in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's highest Sunni Muslim
authority has banned the use of Koranic verses in songs, one day
after a famous Lebanese singer was accused of insulting Islam by
quoting the Koran in his song.
</P>
<P>
The authority said in a statement that the recitation of any
verses from the Koran, the Muslim holy book, was only permitted in
sermons, speeches, praises of God and forms of scientific studies
or instructive literature, the Daily Star reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Any singer who quoted these verses in songs, regardless of
intention, was considered to have been remiss with the words of
God, the authority added.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Beirut's investigating magistrate Abdelrahman
Shihab recommended Marcel Khalife, one of the country's leading
artists, be imprisoned for insulting Islam by quoting Koranic
verses in his songs three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Khalife, 49, is famous in Lebanon and the Arab world as a
whole. His songs were particularly popular among young Lebanese
during Lebanon's 15-year-old civil war that ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, he was first charged with blasphemy by quoting the
Koran in his song "I am Yussef, oh Father," but then Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri ordered the case to be dropped after
widespread protests.
</P>
<P>
Shihab has referred the case to a Beirut criminal court and
proposed that Khalifa be sentenced from six months to three years
in jail.
</P>
<P>
After studying the judge's indictment, the Beirut prosecutor
will set a date for a court hearing.
</P>
<P>
The accusation has sparked strong protests from Lebanese
politicians and intellectuals, who don not see Khalife's song as
violation of Islamic law and will hold a solidarity meeting to
discuss the issue on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
