<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Production Rises Slightly in Bangladesh: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's industrial production
during the 1998-99 fiscal year was only marginally higher than
that in the previous year, The Financial Express newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The growth was only 0.2 percent, much lower than the projected
2.5 percent, the report quoted a review of macro-economic
indicators prepared by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The country's industrial activities followed a generally
declining trend in the first eight months of the 1998-99 fiscal
ending in July 1999, but picked up at an accelerating pace in the
final four months.
</P>
<P>
To improve the situation, the IMF stressed an urgent need for a
coordinated reform agenda which would address the main impediments
to growth, including infrastructural problems, inadequacies in
financial intermediation, labor difficulties and a week financial
base of many industrial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria, however, the
growth rate of the country's manufacturing sector was 2.5 percent,
and the growth of the gross domestic product was 5.2 percent in
the 1998-99 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
