<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian New Assembly Chairman Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Amien Rais, new chairman of the
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), Indonesia's highest
decision-making body, was sworn in here Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Seven new vice chairmen of the MPR were also sworn in
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
The vice chairmen are Matori Abdul Djalil, general chairman of
the National Awakening Party, Kwik Kian Gie, chairman of the
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle, Ginandjar Kartasasmita of
the Golkar Party, Yusuf Amir Faisal of the Crescent Star Party,
Lt. Gen. Hari Sabarno of the Indonesian Military/National Police
faction, Nasri Adlani from the interest group representatives
faction and Husni Thamrin from the United Development Party.
</P>
<P>
Rais, general chairman of the National Mandate Party (PAN), was
voted chairman of the MPR in a neck-to-neck race with Matori on
Sunday night. Rais booked 305 votes, followed closely by Matori
with 279 votes.
</P>
<P>
Rais, a 55-year-old professor in political science, was
nominated by the Reform faction, a coalition of PAN and Justice
Party.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the victory for Rais came as a deal
between the Golkar Party and the alliance of Muslim-based parties
called the "axis force".
</P>
<P>
Rais, who rose to the top of the political scene following his
role in a wave of student demonstrations which helped oust former
president Soeharto in May last year, promised he would continue
the reform agenda.
</P>
<P>
He said he would empower the MPR, which in the past served to
rubber stamp the ruler.
</P>
<P>
"I will introduce a new tradition of summoning the president
every year, not every five years as done in the past," he said.
</P>
<P>
The MPR has a total of 700 members who serve for five years,
including 500 members of the House of Representatives (DPR) and
200 presidential appointees (135 regional representatives and 65
functional representatives).
</P>
<P>
Last week, the MPR agreed to bring forward the presidential
election on October 20 from a scheduled date of November 10, in a
bid to end lingering political uncertainties through the swift
formation of a new, legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
The MPR will then elect vice president on October 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
