<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exports Up 21.1 Percent in August in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' exports rose by
21.1 percent year on year to 3.21 billion U.S. dollars in August,
the highest growth posted since January this year, the National
Statistics Office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
From January to August, export receipts grew by 14.7 percent to
21.86 billion dollars from 19.05 billion dollars a year earlier,
the government statistics office said.
</P>
<P>
Electronic equipment and parts remained the county's top
exports. In August these accounted for 53.7 percent or 1.72
billion dollars of total exports.
</P>
<P>
Computer peripheral units emerged as the second top earner with
sales amounting to 268 million dollars, up 48.3 percent from 180
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
In third spot, articles of wearing apparel and clothing
accessories raked in 251 million dollars, up 8.9 percent from 31
million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of wiring rose by 44.7 percent to 51.37 million
dollars while woodcraft and furniture earned 47.55 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from other manufactured products ranked sixth despite
an 18.4 percent decline to 32.82 million dollars from 40.22
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Rounding up the list of the top ten exports for August were:
metal components, 32.05 million dollars; coconut oil, 23.94
million dollars; petroleum products, 23.11 million dollars; and
bananas, 18.18 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United States remained the Philippines' top export market,
buying 1.02 billion dollars worth or 31.8 percent of total exports
for the month.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the second biggest market with 12.1 percent share,
purchased 388 million dollars, up 16.8 percent over 332 million
dollars a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
