<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Bank Says Japan's Business Sentiment Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Business sentiment among big
Japanese firms improved further in September from three months
earlier amid optimism that Japan's economy will head for
sustainable growth soon, as shown by a quarterly survey released
by the Bank of Japan (BOJ) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese central bank said in its closely watched Tankan
survey of business sentiment that the diffusion index for large
manufacturers improved to minus 22 from minus 37 in the previous
survey in June.
</P>
<P>
The index measures the percentage of companies that believe
business conditions are improving minus the percentage that
believe conditions are worsening. A negative number means
pessimistic corporations outpace optimistic ones.
</P>
<P>
The recovery in business mood marked the third consecutive
quarterly improvement, following a moderate improvement in the
March survey and a sharp rebound in June's poll.
</P>
<P>
Businesses appear to have drawn confidence from the second
consecutive quarterly growth in Japan's gross domestic product (
GDP), posted in the April-June period, although the yen's value
has risen steeply against the dollar since early June.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the index for leading non-manufacturers,
which include the service, construction, real estate, trading and
telecommunications sectors, improved to minus 23 from minus 28.
</P>
<P>
The index for small and medium size manufacturers gained to
minus 40 from minus 46, while that of minor non-manufacturers
firmed to minus 31 from minus 34, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicated that the index for major companies
will continue to improve in the next survey in December.
</P>
<P>
The Tankan survey covered 9,275 Japanese enterprises nationwide,
including 3,871 manufacturers and 5,404 non-manufacturers. Of the
total, 94.4 percent responded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991004.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electric Grid Improvement In East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
has been working on a three-year, 12.35 billion yuan (1.5 billion
US dollars) plan to improve electric grids in its rural areas,
since last November.
</P>
<P>
This year, the province plans to spend 5 billion yuan (600
million US dollars) improving electric grids in more than 12,000
administrative villages and 950 town or township seats.
</P>
<P>
So far it has improved twenty-two 110-kv rural power stations
and electric grids in more than 8,400 administrative villages,
benefiting farmers greatly by cutting the cost of electricity,
allowing an increasing number of them to purchase household
appliances that used to consume more electricity than they could
afford.
</P>
<P>
The improved electric grids have also contributed greatly to
industrial development in rural areas, where there is a growing
number of township enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
