<HEADLINE> Thai PM Summons Anti-terrorism Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai summoned a meeting of the anti-international terrorism
committee on Wednesday to review the Burmese embassy siege and to
reassess the existing security system, " Bangkok Post " reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The National Security Council, The National Intelligence
Agency, military and police intelligence officers took part in
Wednesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Among the points to be discussed would be how the five Burmese
students got into the country, how they brought in war weapons,
who were giving them assistance in Thailand, and who were calling
into the embassy during the siege on Friday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Security agencies will bring up for consideration what should
be done with the 3,000 Burmese students taking asylum in Thailand,
as well as the 250,000 illegal immigrants from Myanmar who work in
factories in provinces bordering Myanmar, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the majority of the Bangkok public polled in a
survey Sunday approved the government's handling of the Burmese
embassy siege and praised Deputy Foreign Minister Sukhumbhand
Paribatra for his personal sacrifice in being exchanged for
hostages.
</P>
<P>
After a 25-hour tense stand-off, the five Burmese students
Saturday ended their siege of the Burmese embassy and freed all
the 38 hostages before they were flown to the Burmese border in
Ratchaburi in the company of Deputy Foreign Minister Sukhumbhand
Paribatra. The students later crossed into Myanmar. 
</P>
