<HEADLINE> China to Provide More Room for Urban Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Offering ideal apartments to
urban families will be a key task for the central government in
the next 10 to 20 years, said an official with the Ministry of
Construction.
</P>
<P>
Xie Jiajin, director-general of the Housing and Real Estate
Industry Department of the Ministry of Construction, said that the
goal is as soon as possible to pair "one family with one apartment
and each person with a separate room with a floor area of at least
13 square meters."
</P>
<P>
Xie said China may expect dramatic housing developments in the
next two decades.
</P>
<P>
To ensure healthy development for the housing market, the
Ministry of Construction has decided to broaden housing reforms
and strengthen housing legislation over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
Next year, the ministry will draft a housing law to ensure the
goal of "apartments for all" will be reached, the director-general
said, adding that the law will also safeguard the rights of
homeowners as properties are bought and sold.
</P>
<P>
From 1949 to 1998, China built apartments in towns and cities
worth 5.24 billion square meters of floor space, and per-capita
living space for urban residents increased from 4.5 square meters
in 1949 to 9.3 square meters last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Xie said, presently more than 30 percent of urban
families are not satisfied with their present apartments, most of
which were given to them according to the old social welfare
system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
