<DOCNO> XIE19991004.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Province Recommended to Global Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan Province in Southwest
China has been strongly recommended by the World Bank to global
investors.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted a recent WB report that the
investment environment in western Sichuan almost measures up to
that of the Yangtze and Pearl river deltas, and that investment
here has grown despite slumps elsewhere in Asia.
</P>
<P>
It is one of China's hinterland regions that investors should
tap first, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The WB recommends Sichuan because the province boasts abundant
natural resources and an improved investment environment, Deputy
Provincial Governor Li Dachang was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Located in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, Sichuan
covers 485,000 sq km, which is 5.1 percent of China's total area.
It is the country's third most populous province with nearly 85
million people.
</P>
<P>
Since China adopted economic reforms and opening up policies in
the late 1970s, Sichuan has witnessed unprecedented economic
development. Its economic potential makes it the most powerful
province in western China.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the province's gross domestic product was 358 billion
yuan (43 billion U.S. dollars), 4.5 percent of the national total
and 10th in the country.
</P>
<P>
The province has drawn up preferential policies to encourage
foreign investment. In 1998, it attracted about 1.6 billion U.S.
dollars in contractual foreign funds, while in the first half of
this year, contractual foreign funds rose 104 percent over the
same period last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
