<DOCNO> XIE19991004.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria's Ruling Party Maintains Top Position in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Austria's ruling Socialist
Democratic Party maintained the top position in the parliamentary
election Sunday, but only captured 33.4 percent of the votes, down
4.7 percentage points from the last election, according to
preliminary results released by the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
With 27.2 percent of the votes, the right-wing Freedom Party
led by Joerg Haider rose to the second place to become the biggest
winner in the election, up 5.2 percentage points from the last
election.
</P>
<P>
The conservative Austrian People's Party of Foreign Minister
Wolfgang Schuessel dropped to the third place with 26.9 percent of
the votes, down 1.4 percent points.
</P>
<P>
The Greens joined the winners with a gain of 2.3 percentage
points to reach 7.1 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
If the results are confirmed, the Social Democrats will hold 65
seats in the 183-member parliament, a loss of six. Haider's
Freedom Party will gain 12 seats to take 53 seats. The People's
Party will keep its 52 seats, while the Greens took four more to
13 seats.
</P>
<P>
Before the election, Chancellor Viktor Klima had ruled out the
possibility of a coalition with Haider's Freedom Party if his
Social Democratic Party failed to gain the absolute majority.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Schuessel had said he would honor his pre-election
pledge to go into opposition if his party finishes the third.
</P>
<P>
Media commentators here said Klima will find it very difficult
for his much weakened Social Democratic Party to form a coalition
with the only choice left -- the Greens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
