<DOCNO> XIE19991004.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Deserts Formed Seventy Million Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China's deserts began to form
some 70 million years ago and have evolved from a red color to
today's yellow, according to deserts experts from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Because of a warm subtropical climate during the Cretaceous
Period (about 70 million years ago), there was a red desert belt
from the Northwest to the Southeast, notes Dong Guangrong, a
researcher of CAS's Lanzhou Desert Institute.
</P>
<P>
Since the Quaternary Period (about two million years ago),
northern China has had comparatively cooler temperatures and a
yellow desert evolved in a vast area in the North in an area that
is prone to drought.
</P>
<P>
China's deserts now cover a 1.1 million sq km area, or 11.4
percent of China's total area, most of them in Xinjiang, Qinghai,
Gansu, Inner Mongolia, and Shaanxi in the North and Northwest.
</P>
<P>
China has some of the largest amount of desert land, but there
have been no definite explanations of desert evolution in the past.
So, CAS began its desert research in 1978 and scientists
eventually began to work out China's desert history.
</P>
<P>
Researches have shown that geological structure and climate
changes were the major causes of most deserts in the world, but
the man's destructive activities done to the natural environment
has helped increase desertification.
</P>
<P>
In order to halt desertification, the Lanzhou Desert Institute
is now doing researches on desert developmental and evolutionary
trends with a database.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
