<DOCNO> XIE19991004.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Town Claims 24 Million Dollars for Cablecar Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Cavalese, a northern Italian ski
resort, has claimed 44 billion lire (about 24 million U.S. dollars)
from the government in compensation for the cablecar tragedy that
occurred at the resort early last year.
</P>
<P>
On February 3, 1998, 20 tourists aboard a cablecar were killed
when the tail-fin of a U.S. Marine EA-6B Prowler surveillance
plane sliced the ski-lift cable above the Cermis mountain during a
ground-hugging training flight from a NATO air base in nearby
Aviano.
</P>
<P>
The claim includes 28 billion lire (about 15 million dollars)
to the owner-operator of the cablecar service.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the London Convention covering NATO
operations and liabilities in a NATO country, the Italian Defense
Ministry should pay for the compensation cost, which will be
shared by Italy and the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
