<DOCNO> XIE19991004.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Suffers Big Blow in Premier League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Manchester
United suffered a big blow at the English premier league here on
Sunday, when they were whitewashed 5-0 by Chelsea on road.
</P>
<P>
It was the first premier league defeat for the European
champions since December 1998 and their worst loss for three years.
</P>
<P>
The Treble winners also had Nicky Butt sent off in the match as
he was dismissed in the 23rd minute after a retaliatory kick at
Dennis Wise, who had floored his fellow midfielder with a high
tackle in the Stamford Bridge clash.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea had already swept into a 2-0 lead by that time with a
strike after just 28 seconds from Uruguayan Gustavo Poyet and a
headed goal from Chris Sutton in the 16th minute.
</P>
<P>
United, whose last league defeat was a 3-2 setback against
Middlesbrough at Old Trafford on December 19, simply could not
cope with Chelsea's fast, flowing football.
</P>
<P>
Poyet added his second after 55 minutes before an own goal by
Norwegian Henning Berg three minutes later and an 82nd minute
strike from Jody Morris completed United's misery.
</P>
<P>
Their new goalkeeper, Italian Massimo Taibi, looked especially
vulnerable as they plunged to their first defeat in 46 matches in
all competitions.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea manager Gianluca Vialli said: "I'm very happy with our
performance. You're never perfect but we almost were today. We
kept our concentration for 90 minutes and that's why we scored
five and let in none.
</P>
<P>
"We have to keep our feet firmly on the ground. Nothing has
changed. We are closer but we are still behind them (Manchester
United)."
</P>
<P>
United's thrashing, their worst defeat since losing 5-0 to
Newcastle in October 1996, also cost them the league leadership.
</P>
<P>
Leeds United took over at the top, coming from behind to win 2-
1 at Watford with goals from Michael Bridges in the 45th minute
and Australian Harry Kewell on 70th minute.
</P>
<P>
Leeds have 22 points, second-placed United have 21 and
Sunderland are third on 20, all from 10 games. Fourth-placed
Chelsea are on 19 with two matches in hand.
</P>
<P>
England striker Alan Shearer brought his goal tally to 10 in
his last four domestic and European games by scoring after 17th
and 45th minutes as Newcastle beat Middlesbrough 2-1 at St James's
Park.
</P>
<P>
Defender Gerry Taggart grabbed a 76th minute winner for
Leicester in a see-saw match at Tottenham Hotspur.
</P>
<P>
Leicester led after 25 minutes from a Mussy Izzet spot kick but
Norwegian Steffen Iversen fired the London club ahead with goals
on 26th and 35th minutes.
</P>
<P>
Izzet equalised in the 68th minute before Taggart dealt the
decisive blow eight minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Italian Paolo di Canio struck after 30th and 72nd minutes to
fire West Ham to a 2-1 victory at home to London neighbours
Arsenal, who had Patrick Vieira and Marc Vivien-Foe sent off in
the last 10 minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
